This shocked kiteboarder really did hit a hump in the road - as he rode right over a giant HUMPBACK WHALE
 
Having initially been gliding innocently across the water, Andrei Grigoriev's incredible footage then shows the exact moment he then collided with the large mammal.
 
Andrei's board skims right over the back of the rising whale, before the extreme sports enthusiast can be seen spreading his arms in utter amazement.
 
The moment was captured in the waters off Crissy Field Beach, California, USA, on June 18, 2017.
 
Andrei, 36, who lives in the Bay Area, said he had never even seen a whale before that moment, and though the footage may appear shocking, he never intended any harm to the animal; it was a complete accident.

description.original:
ID: 1548040

Mike Korostelev, 35, from Moscow was on a photography journey in Tonga in September 2018 was lucky enough to photograph the beautiful humpback whales on their annual birthing journey from Antarctica.

From the months of July through to October, the humpbacks spend their time in the heated waters before making the journey back to the Arctic waters.

Speaking of the magical scene, Korostelev, said “As you see in the pics from the copter sometimes the mums have an escort – adult male whale. He is guarding the mum and kid and waiting when she gets free again to be able to copulate again

“The whales behave differently with humans – but never aggressive. Sometimes they just don’t notice you. The baby whales are very curious and try to play with you.

SUBSCRIBE: http://bit.ly/Oc61Hj 
We upload a new incredible video every weekday. Subscribe to our YouTube channel so you don't miss out:


A British diver used a flying drone to capture incredible footage of humpback whales and their calves swimming off the coast of Tonga, in September 2014. The aerial camera shows a protective whale mother and her adorable calf as well as bull males chasing a female in an ocean mating ritual. Darren Rice, 47, moved from Crawley, West Sussex, five-years-ago to run a dive resort on the island of Foa in the Ha'apai region of the Kingdom of Tonga. The former underwater camera operator shot the footage during five hours over two days and flew the drone from a small boat driven by his wife Nina.

description.original:
In recent years big shoals of herring were gathering in Norwegian Fjords from November until January. Following them are Orcas and Humpback whales, who are hunting together for herring with their individual "special techniques".
Orcas are performing "killer loops" or „carousel feeding“ in which they swim fast into the shoal of herring, turn around their own axis and beat the fish with their tail. 
The paralyzed fish then float in the water and are easy to pick up by the Killer whales or birds. The Humpback whales dive under the herring and taking a huge gulp while ascending. 

This 4k + footage was shot around Vengsoya / Norway with drones and Underwater and is featured in the new BBC Blue Planet 2 series.

Please subscribe, if you like it!

This drone footage was captured on March 5th 2019 off the coast of San Diego, California. This was the first time I have ever seen a humpback whale feeding aggregation in San Diego waters. The vast majority of our humpback whale sightings involve whales that are merely passing through. While we do see whales occasionally grab a snack if it's available, to see as many as twenty whales lunge feeding on the surface is simply something we do not see virtually ever in San Diego!

description.original:
Seems like these humpback whales had a lunge date! Whale watchers in Monterey Bay were treated to a whale of a show yesterday, as over a dozen dashing diners took turns launching and lunching on anchovy antipasti! 

Humpback whales are here to gorge on the bounty of the Monterey Bay’s cool waters before heading down to warmer Mexican waters to breed. Their expandable throat pouches engulf gallons upon gallons of fishy seawater, before powerful tongues push the soup through mustache-like baleen, leaving only the finest of anchovy noodles behind these built-in pasta strainers.

Fun fact: Our whales are a different population than the humpbacks in Hawai'i, which migrate to Alaska and back.

Go whale watching if you can! Late summer is a magical time of year in Monterey Bay.

____

Shocking footage has emerged of a man swimming dangerously close to two humpback whales.
 
In the clip, the daredevil can be seen swimming out to the whales, and he even touches one of them.
 
The whale can be seen lifting its head after being prodded but then proceeds to circle the swimmer.
 
Harassing whales in the wild is an illegal offence under the Marine Mammal Protection Act, as it is seen as harmful to the animals.

description.original: While fishing around the island of Tonga we discovered a tangled mother humpback whale with a calf. We hopped in the water to help but had a hard time getting close. We were determined to help this whale, hearing an animal of that size crying underwater is the saddest thing I have seen and heard. The final moments of freedom were not captured on film but we successful in removing the buoys and anchor from the mother whale.
title.original: Tangled Mother Humpback Whale Needs Help

description.original: During our Antarctic cruise on 21st Feb 2018 while in Wilhelmina Bay on National Geographic Explorer ship we were taken on a zodiac ride by Eric Guth to see the whales. As we approached the feeding whales one humpback whale breached in front of us. We then turned off the engine and watched the whales. Within minutes two humpback whales approached our zodiac, and for the next half an hour they "played" with our boat, coming very close but with out touching or disturbing our little inflatable boat in any way. It was an amazing experience.
title.original: close encounter with Humpback Whales

description.original:
In Tonga, we got to experience one of the most amazing things we've ever done in our lives: swim with humpback whales.  We'd organized a tour with a local dive company (it's illegal to swim with them on your own) and got incredibly lucky as we found a mother, her calf and an accompanying male.  We probably spent an hour and a half in the water with them and the calf put on quite a show for us!

After our whale swim, we spent another week enjoying Tonga with several boats who all had crews all under the age of 40.  Keep an eye out, you may see a few familiar faces!  ;)  We had a great time with the group I jokingly referring to as the "Kid's Table Club" but eventually the wind filled in enough that it was time for us to leave Tonga.  We had such a blast here that it was hard to leave!

To follow along with our cruising adventures, please subscribe to our YouTube channel and check out our blog and Facebook page:

Whale Alert from Dana Point- Since Sunday 7/20 we have been seeing this spirited pair of Humpback Whales , along the shores of Dana Point, Laguna and San Clemente they are just going back and forth making Dana Point their home - we would love it if they stayed!  Kind of like a little Monterey Bay show off Dana Point, Capt Frank videoed this pair with both his Phantom 2 Copter cam and his Cannon camera , all the boats in this area are at a dead stop , because humpbacks are very friendly and like to approach better to stay put.. so our passengers can see what the whales look like above the surface and at the surface. Dana Wharf is the premiere year-round whale watching company in Dana Point. Beginning in 1971 we are the pioneer of whale watching adventures in Orange County, California.

In addition to whales, thousands of dolphins, sea lions, sea faring birds and even sharks are found year-round in our waters, so we always have plenty of wildlife to see.

description.original:
Live webcam feed from the Hawaiian Islands Humpback Whale Marine Sanctuary off the island of Maui.  The Sanctuary, which spans all the way to the mysterious island of Molokai and Lanai in the distance, is the birthing and mating grounds of the North Pacific Humpback Whale population.  They can be seen breaching, fin and tail slapping in large numbers here from December to April.  This live feed rotates from north (tiny Mokuho'Oniki Island and Kahana, Maui), west (Island of Molokai) to south (Island of Lanai)

Just in front is the Kahekili Marine Reserve - one of only three conservation zones on Maui and a popular spot for watching green sea turtles feed on seaweed.  Spot the occasional pod of dolphins or a rare sighting of the critically endangered Hawaiian Monk Seal.   Morning rainbows are common and the sunsets in the evening are spectacular.

This is the exact view that guests of Maui Sands Unit 4B experience right from the ground floor lanai.  Unit 4B is a carbon neutral,  eco-friendly and fully-equipped condo.  Maui Sands is one of the original condo resorts in all of West Maui and it has retained a lot of the old Hawaii vintage feel of the 60's before the hotel boom.    If you would like to experience this view in person, visit http://www.mauisands.com to find out more.

The researchers at the Hawaiian Islands Humpback Whale Marine Sanctuary at NOAA has asked for your help in spotting Humpback Whales. Specifically, they want our viewers to report anything unusual with the Humpbacks such as vessel strikes, entanglements etc. If you spot a humpback and more importantly see one in distress, please make note of the day and time (time on the bottom left of video) and email the details to whalesighting@mauisands.com. We will forward your report right away to the Maui Island coordinator at NOAA.

If you spot any other marine creatures such as Hawaiian Monk Seals, Spinner Dolphins or Sea Turtles (Green or Hawksbill) feel free to report it in the live chat.  

Chat Rules: English only, no retractions please.

description.original:
Whale watchers aboard a catamaran with Captain Dave’s Dolphin and Whale Safari were viewing a humpback whale when they noticed that the whale seemed to be playing with a shrimp trap buoy located about 2 and 1/2 miles off the coast of Dana Point, California. Several minutes later the whale dove down and entangled itself around the tail.

For several nail-biting minutes the humpback whale thrashed violently to remove the line, tossing the line and buoy high into the air. Eventually the animal managed to snap the polypropylene line and free itself from the entanglement to rowdy cheers. One passenger even cried with relief. 

“I have never seen a whale as dangerous as that whale was when it was thrashing around. I wouldn’t have wanted to be anywhere near it.  I happened to have my high-speed camera and I filmed at 240 frames per second the very last violent maneuver this whale did when it freed itself,” said Captain Dave. I was so relieved for the whale and myself as it meant I did not have to spend the rest of the day out on the water trying to free this ticked off whale with our local Whale disentanglement group, the OC Whale Rescue Team! Everyone on all three whale watching boats cheered it was one of the most beautiful moments I have ever had on the water!”

Nearly 1,000 dolphins and whales worldwide die every day because of fishing gear entanglement. In 2015 over 50 entangled whales were seen off the coast of California according to the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, (NOAA).  Captain Dave helped organize Orange County's first whale disentanglement group in 2008.

One shrimp trap buoy has a series of up to 12 traps laid out on the bottom of the ocean with weights in between each trap. If the whale had not broken free it would have been hard, if not impossible, for the whale to go very far dragging all that gear. It appears that all the line was removed. It’s unknown at this time if the animal sustained any serious injuries to the tail.

Humpback whales were once a rare sighting off of Dana Point. Since 2014 they have been seen in record numbers.  Humpback whales are known for their playfulness and easily recognized by their long pectoral flippers. They filter up to 3,000 pounds of food, usually krill or small fish, through plates of black baleen that hang from the top of the upper jaw. Humpbacks reach about 50 feet in length and weigh up to 40 tons. 

In addition to humpback whales like the one in this video, huge numbers of migrating gray whales are being seen off the coast of Southern California right now. In a span of just four days, Captain Dave’s Dolphin and Whale Safari’s excursions have had 150 encounters. The next two weekends Dana Point Harbor will celebrate gray whales and other marine wildlife at the 45th annual Festival of Whales. Ocean-themed events and activities that have an emphasis on education and environmental responsibility are planned for the two-weekend festival.

Captain Dave exclaimed, “I saw 26 gray whales during my first trip today. A personal record!”


All audio and video footage is copyright David Anderson/DolphinSafari.com and may not be used without permission.

description.original:
Filmed on the 28th of March this year...2019....I spotted this beautiful creature whilst I and Carla Regler, friend and fellow photographer were on the stunning cliffs at Lands End, Cornwall, UK . She was flying her drone at the time and i was watching it and the area for safety purpose....when out the corner of my eye i saw the huge humpback break the surface and blast its vapourised breath into the air. She sent her drone out to film immediately whilst I prepared mine for take off. Both drones had polarising filters on them, tho differing NDs. 
The whale was swimming at some pace and it was not long before we had reached our legal limit for distance so had to stop.
I have edited this video with some of the footage I took prior to the whale arriving and you too can see how beautiful the surroundings are.
title.original: Amazing rare drone footage of a humpback whale off the Cornish coast

description.original:
Michael Fishbach, co-founder of The Great Whale Conservancy (GWC), narrates his encounter with a young humpback whale entangled in local fishing nets.

At first, the animal appeared to be dead, yet Fishbach investigated and quickly discovered that the poor creature was tangled in a fishing net.

The humans had to act fast; what began as a tragedy soon became a thrilling rescue as Fishbach and his crew labored to free the young whale.

The entire encounter was caught on videotape and later narrated by Fishbach himself.

Watch as the whale named Valentina by her rescuers goes from near death to freedom, then rewards her saviours with dozens of magnificent full-body breeches and tail flips.

Indeed, this video has the power to inspire action on behalf of other beings. In ways big and small, each of us can be the one who helps another.

Opportunities to be a hero for animals are all around.

Please check out http://www.eii.org/gwc/ for more great information on Great Whale Conservancy

Full story on this awesome rescue here http://wakeup-world.com/2011/07/17/whale-shows-amazing-appreciation-after-being-freed-from-fishing-nets/
title.original: Humpback Whale Shows AMAZING Appreciation After Being Freed From Nets

description.original:
On Sunday afternoon, about eight miles off the coast of Dana Point, our whale watching vessel operated by Captain Tom encountered an entangled humpback whale.

When our boat first found this whale, it was obviously very stressed and it was doing tail slashes. The whale did over 100 tail slashes, a violent maneuver as seen in the video. 

It was most likely trying to remove the remainder of the gear, or maybe it was feeling a lot more freedom from having had some of that gear removed earlier in the day. Captain Tom told me that he could see rope wrapped around its body and trailing behind it, although it was hard to tell if the whale still had rope wrapped around it or if they were scars from the entanglement. We definitely know it still has some rope attached.

*****
Captain Dave's Dolphin and Whale Watching Safari offers daily, year-round, dolphin and whale watching trips from Dana Point, California, aboard a hi-tech catamaran sailboat with Eye-to-Eye Underwater Viewing Pods.

description.original: A Wildlife guide and photographer to polar destinations sharing his passion for nature. Learn about the wildlife and how to be a better nature photographer. This Pagophilia vlog takes you swimming with whales in the fjords of Norway. Here, Humpback whales sometimes follow the Orcas hunting for Herring (a type of fish) and let the Orca do all the work gathering the Herring but the Humpback then come and steel their food. Another technique is that Humpbacks push the Herring towards the shore and very shallow water. This traps the Herring and the Humpback can feed without the Herring has any escape routes. Sometimes it is so shallow that there is barely enough water for the Humpback to swim - let alone for a Humpback and a snorkeller like myself. Watch this extraordinary film and learn about the Humpbacks and the Orcas visiting the fjords of Norway during a few short winter months.

description.original: We were watching over 1,500 dolphins of two species; Pacific White-Sided Dolphins and Northern Right Whale Dolphins. The second type are rare to see except we see them periodically in Monterey Bay due to deep water so close to shore. Theses dolphins are unusual and are shaped like torpedoes, have no dorsal fin, and are all black with a white underside. On this day they had some small gray calves with them. This large school of dolphins encounters a mother and calf Humpback Whale and some dolphins began to “snout ride” of them. That’s when dolphins, which are very playful and intelligent, annoy the Humpbacks a bit by buzzing around their head and causing the large whales to move quickly forward allowing the dolphins to surf off the wave created by the whale’s head. The dolphins seem to really enjoy this and the whales aren’t really bothered. The Humpback calf was born in Mexico about 4 months ago and now he’s here with mom in Monterey Bay to learn how to catch fish and krill. In this case the little whale is experiencing the excitement of swimming around hundreds of dolphins! For Use Must Ask and Credit Monterey Bay Whale Watch/ Gowhales.com (Video by Jason Berring)
title.original: Over 1,500 Dolphins Snout-Ride on Mom/Calf Humpback Whales in Monterey Bay

Enjoy a magical evening cruise that features guaranteed whale viewing and great food. Following a short motor coach ride to scenic Auke Bay, you'll board a deluxe catamaran specially designed for wildlife viewing. Relax in the warm, spacious main cabin as you set out to explore Stephens Passage, a pristine marine wilderness surrounded by snow-capped peaks and glaciers. This area is world-renowned as a favored summer feeding ground for humpback whales. As whales are sighted, your skilled captain will gently maneuver the vessel to allow exceptional viewing opportunities. You'll be amazed by the gracefulness of these ocean giants as they slowly arc their massive tail flukes into the air. The whales are often close enough to hear them breathe. If conditions allow, an underwater hydrophone will be deployed so that you can experience their incredible "singing." An on-board naturalist will explain the behavior and habitat of the humpback whale, and other wildlife you may encounter, including killer whales (orcas), sea lions, porpoise, harbor seals and bald eagles. Throughout the voyage you'll be treated to a delicious variety of appetizers including a baron of beef, reindeer sausage, smoked salmon, cheese and vegetable trays, hot shrimp dip, dessert bars and pastries. Tea, coffee and cocoa will be served. Beer, wine and sodas are available at an additional charge. The operators of this tour guarantee you will see a whale. If not, you'll receive a $100 cash refund as you disembark the tour vessel. In the past ten plus years, whales have been sighted on every tour

description.original:
In late August '02 an adult humpback whale became entangled in shark mesh off the QLD Gold Coast. The whale disappeared dragging the heavy net and was not expected to survive.

Three days later the animal was relocated off Yamba in NSW with net wrapped around its head including the blowhole and a large mass of net rope and floats binding the tail stock.
In a combined operation Sea World, the QLD Department of Primary Industries together with the NSW Fisheries, Marine Parks Authority and the National Parks and Wildlife Service were able to cut the material from the whale.

During the operation to free the whale it was closely accompanied by three other adult humpback whales.
title.original: Humpback whale disentanglement

description.original:
Beautiful drone video of a humpback whale mother and calf. The whales 'blow rainbows' and give 'a wave' with it's tail.

A dramatic increase of humpback whale sightings off the coast of Dana Point, in Southern California, is causing excitement among whale watchers and tour operators alike. According to our we've had 42 encounters with humpbacks so far this month, compared with just 4 last January.

Dana Point’s whale watching industry started many years ago with the gray whale migration. And Dana Point locals and visitors know January to be a great time to view gray whales making their annual journey from waters near Alaska to the lagoons of Baja, Mexico. And now it seems as though humpback whales want in on the fun, too! Humpback whales can be seen near Dana Point throughout the year.

Humpback whales are migrating from their mating and calving grounds near Mexico and Central America to Dana Point to feed on krill and small schooling fish. The whales filter up to 3,000 pounds of food per day through plates of baleen that hang from their upper jaw. Humpback whales can weigh up to 40 tons and are well known for their incredible and acrobatic surface behaviors such as breaching and tail slapping.

Filmed by Grayden Fanning

description.original:
While on a whale watching tour off the West Side of Oahu, HI we saw a pod of about 7 humpback whales. This was towards the end of whale season and were told it was "last call at the bar". Most of the single whale females had started to head back to Alaska, but the few that were left were being heavily pursued by the males. After watching them come up to the surface for air a few times it was neat to sometimes see the tail flip up out of the water. It was an exciting morning, but we were all a little disappointed that none had breached. We started to head back, and that's when we noticed they had started to follow us, and had one final goodbye... Make sure to check out 1:15 - 1:45

The amazing tour we took was "Best of the West" at sailhawaii.com

MANDATORY ONSCREEN CREDIT - Whale Watching Sydney

WHALE would you look at the time! These huge humpbacks were keen to get on the road to continue their migration – and gave a boatload of tourists a wave goodbye.
 
Snapper Jonas Liebschner captured the incredible moment the whales waved at tourists in Sydney harbour, Australia, as they began their migration north for the year this week.
 
Around 30,000 humpbacks are believed to head away from the Antarctic towards warmer waters at this time of year and German-born Jonas, who takes tourists out to spot the gigantic mammals on a whale-watching boat, was delighted at the reaction his guests got.
 
In his footage, a whale breaches high from the water before crashing back down while in another picture the boat full of tourists can be seen watching on in awe as one whale appears to give them a wave.

description.original:
Humpback whales are one of the most massive and beautiful creatures on earth. They come to Tonga in July through October to mate and to have their babies in a safe environment where there are no predators. The conditions are ideal and the mothers feed their calves massive amounts fo milk so they will grow rapidly. They will need their size and strength for the long journey to northern waters where they feed. Bulls, or male humpbacks, also come to Tonga and they will follow females and calves for weeks, providing an escort and added safety for the pair. But they are also waiting and hoping for a chance to mate with the females. Their protectiveness is only partially out of desire to keep her and the calf safe. It is also motivated by a desire for an opportunity to reproduce. When a female humpback is ready to mate, males will follow and even chase her, competing with each other for the rights. These pursuits often involve six or seven males swimming at full speed, acting very aggressively as they thrash and bump each other. Occasionally, they inflict serious injury on each other in the process. They are 60 ton animals and their hormones are raging. They have little restraint and a lot of drive as they struggle ferociously to impress the female. These behaviors are thrilling and fascinating to watch from a boat. These swimmers are enjoying a snorkel in the shallow waters near an island in the Tongan waters. They have been watching the whales from the boat and looking for a chance to actually swim with a whale. Now, during a break for lunch, they are looking at coral and fish along the reef. It is the last place you would expect to see a humpback whale. But the whales came crashing through like a herd of wild elephants. The female led the pack and nearly struck two of the swimmers. They saw her coming in time to swim backwards and out of the way. The laws here, as well as common sense, require that people avoid getting closer that 5m or 15 feet to the whales. Ethical guides such as the one on this tour will strictly enforce these rules and make sure that guests understand. But it is impossible to control the behavior of the whales and it is possible that they will not respect the same distance. The swimmer filming this incredible event looked to his left to see a 55 foot humpback bearing down on him in water that was barely deep enough for the whale to squeeze through. He was floating at the surface, about 15 feet off the coral and there was nothing to do but tuck in his arms and legs. The whale seemed to realize he was about to collide with a helpless person and he slowed abruptly, twisting and almost scraping the coral with his belly. The bull swam directly under him and missed by inches. This gentle giant actually made very slow and careful strokes with his tail until he was clear of the swimmer. He then accelerated with much bigger tail strokes and rapidly took off after the pack. A total of seven whales barged past these surprised swimmers. These incredible creatures have much greater intelligence and compassion than we have ever given them credit for. Sadly, some countries are still hunting and killing these magnificent animals. The Tongan people can teach us a lot about respecting the whales and the environment. The humpbacks also provide the Tongans with much needed revenue through tourism as people travel here to experience their beauty in their natural world. To lose these whales would be beyond tragic.

Source & embed code: https://rumble.com/v7zuvn-gentle-humpback-whale-on-heat-run-shows-remarkable-compassion-for-swimmer-i.html.

description.original:
I have been waiting all year for humpback whales as they migrate from Mexico to Alaska during summer months.  The last 3 days was the hottest weather here in Northern California, which caused many school of fish to move closer towards the coast.  Humpback whales tend to follow their meals and I spotted hundreds of humpback whales about a mile off the coast.  I really love these whales, they are so huge and lovely creatures.

I used my Mavic 2 Pro.   It is actually REALLY HARD to take shots of these humpback whales as the waters here in Northern California are very muddy and the whales will disappear completely once they go under water.  This is about 6-8 hours of flying trying to catch them when on the surface so please hit the thumbs up as it was a LOT of flying, thanks!

All the shots are off coast of Pacifica, California where I live, if you want to capture some whale shots, fly towards the ocean about a mile out when the weather is warm.    When weather is cold, the humpback whales won't be easy to spot as they will be further in the ocean.

How big are these humpback whales?  See 5:22, which shows a seal next to a humpback whale swimming thru.  They are about the size of a school bus yes. 

#humpbackwhales #whales #mavic2pro

description.original: The body of a dead juvenile humpback whale washed ashore in Turnagain Arm just past Girdwood along the Seward Highway on Monday. Scientists say the whale may have followed fish or beluga whales into the arm and wasn’t able to turn back. The whale beached close to the Seward Highway, so the animal won’t go to waste and its blubber will be used by members of various Alaska Native groups. The location also enables biologists access for collecting tissue and organ samples.
title.original: Scientists conduct research on dead humpback whale along Turnagain Arm

description.original: Eye-popping footage of a recent rare close encounter with a humpback whale off the coast of BC's spectacular Great Bear Rainforest. Whales like this one and many other coastal species are at grave risk from Enbridge's proposed pipeline to pump oil from the Tar Sands across BC and into supertankers in Kitimat, before plying some of the world's most treacherous waters en route to Asia.  This awesome creature approached a boat carrying among others filmmaker Damien Gillis, and proceeded to interact playfully with the crew for 45 minutes!  Watch highlights of this amazing and unique west coast experience - caught on camera.
title.original: Close Encounter with a Humpback Whale

A massive humpback whale was caught in a buoy line off the coast of California. An eel fisherman was captured on video jumping on the whales back to rescue it. 'That one rope was still holding him down to the ocean floor, and the whole time he was swimming in very tight counter-clockwise circles because all that rope was still attached to the bottom of the ocean,' one of the crew members said. At one point, the whale kicked his tail, nearly smashing into the boat. 'That one rope was still holding him down to the ocean floor, and the whole time he was swimming in very tight counter-clockwise circles because all that rope was still attached to the bottom of the ocean,' Nicholas said.

description.original:
At least 16 humpback whales harassed 11 killer whales after the killer whales killed a gray whale calf in Monterey Bay, CA. Although the calf died within a few minutes after we arrived, humpbacks  continued to harass the killer whales for over 6 hours:  could they have been trying to protect the dead calf? NEW RECORD: This  is the longest known interaction between feeding killer whales and mobbing humpbacks. The tightly grouped humpbacks made loud trumpeting sounds, rolled and slashed their pectoral flippers and flukes, and closely approached (and even chased) the killer whales. The humpbacks were still interacting with the killer whales when we left them near sunset. 

Filmed by killer whale researcher Alisa Schulman-Janiger (California Killer Whale Project) from the Point Sur Clipper (Monterey Bay Whale Watch) on 3 May 2012. With Captain Nancy Black (killer whale researcher) and deckhand/videographer Mike Merlo.

Link: Please see Candace Calloway Whiting's September 2015 Huffington Post story "Humpback Whales Intervene in Killer Whale Attacks on a Baby Gray Whale, and Save Seals", for photos and more details about humpback whales interfering with killer whales - both in this encounter and in a killer whale attack on a seal in Antarctica (documented by NOAA scientists Bob  Pitman and John Durban). Neuroscientist Dr. Lori Marino shares her opinions about these encounters; she is a renowned expert in the cognitive ability of whales and dolphins.
http://www.huffingtonpost.com/candace-calloway-whiting/humpback-whales-intervene_b_8093080.html
title.original: Killer Whales Prey On Gray Whale Calf, Humpbacks Interfere; Monterey Bay CA

description.original:
Dedicated to "STELLWAGEN BANK NMS"  Sept 2014
 
Special thanks to the Captain Jeff Eagan,the crew members: Tasia Blough-Naturalist & Photographer, Don Johnson, Larry McNamara, the remaining crew members & visitors on the boat named “AURORA” of the New England Aquarium Whale Watch from Boston, MA. telephone 617-973-5206. www.neaq.org

For my family & in loving memory of my husband Arthur David Belden-Naturalist.

by:Michelle Belden–Naturalist-Texas- mbelden50@yahoo.com.
Video duration: 14.56 minutes Please enjoy the video.                                                                                                                          

Every year the humpback whales migrate in the Atlantic Ocean from the Maritime Provinces of Canada, pass through Maine, Massachusetts, New York, Florida, Cuba and the Dominican Republic.  They feed out of the Stellwagen Bank National Marine Sanctuary down to the Silver Bank Sanctuary for Marine Mammals. The Stellwagen Bank National Marine Sanctuary is an underwater plateau in the Atlantic Ocean surrounded by the Gulf of Maine, Massachusetts Bay and Cape Cod Bay. The Silver Bank Sanctuary is also, an underwater plateau located in the Caribbean Ocean near Samana Bay and is a territory of the Dominican Republic. Both of these Sanctuaries are enriched with biodiversity, abundant schools of fish and plenty of krill, anchovies, cod, herring, pollock and capelin for the vigorous appetite of a baleen feeding marine mammal.
The New England Aquarium out of Boston, Massachusetts runs cruises to enrich our lives and educate the public to see the endangered Humpback Whales at the Stellwagen Bank NMS.  On September 23, 2014 my sister and I boarded the catamaran named “AURORA” and left the Boston harbor. It was a sunny day, calm seas and the wind favorable.  It took 1 hour to travel 35 miles off the mainland to the southwest corner of Stellwagen Bank NMS region which is north of the Cape Cod Bay. Everyone on the boat was engaged in watching humpback whale behavior.
1. We saw humpback whales “Spouting” which is spraying water and breathing through their blow hole. 
2.  “Logging” on the surface of the ocean, which is a state of whales resting or sleeping in the surf. 
3.  “Breaching” was seen in the distance. This is when the entire power of the whale propels out of the surface of the ocean and slams back down into the depths of the sea.
4.  “FLIPPERING” activity which is when they slap their pectoral flippers on the surface of the ocean making a loud splashing sound.
5.  “SPYHOP” which is when the humpback whale peeks only their head and eyes out of the water and look briefly, turning their heads to the right and left, and then disappear back into the ocean. 
6. “FLUKE-UP and “FLUKE-DOWN” is when the humpback whales expose their tails at the surface of the ocean going into a dive. 
7.  “LOUD TRUMPETING” is when the humpback sprays from their blowhole and making a loud sound. It is interpreted this type of sound maybe communicating tension or anxiety. 
While we were all involved in watching these outstanding marine mammal behaviors, the unexpected gift was given to our boat the “AURORA” to witness. We saw a group of five whales swimming together, breathing, spouting, trumpeting, fluke diving, and each one made their presence known. Each one gracefully descending into a deep dive.  Each Humpback whale did a progressive dive into the depths of the ocean; we watched the first as it exposed it’s fluke and then dive. The second, the third, the fourth and the very last one, which was the fifth whale, did it’s last descending dive into the ocean. Everyone on the boat cheered, the captain sounded the horn for the finale of a great moment. What a memorable encounter with the endangered humpback whales. We saw 12 humpback whales this exceptional day. 

Added Commentary from Naturalist Tasia Blough from the New England Aquarium: “The whale called “Habanero” was the first whale we saw in a whale behavior state called logging.  “Habanero” is female and was born to a whale named “Pepper”  in the year 2000. “Pepper” was one of the first two whales cataloged in the world named “Salt” and “Pepper”. The breaching whales were “Northstar” and “Hatchmark”. The whale named “Northstar” has a relatively a fresh wound on his back, likely due to a vessel strike from the summer. The group of whales swimming beside the boat named Aurora, was “Milkweed” and her calf, “Perseid” and her calf, “Storm” and “Pleats”.  The whale named “Pleats” also has laceration scars down its back from a vessel strike.”

The New England Aquarium Whale Watch  and Boston Harbor Cruises are participating companies in “Whale SENSE” program that have high standards in practices of viewing whales, providing education,ocean stewardship & conservation-www.whalesense.org

description.original: This is a short video of selected clips of humpback whales slapping their pectoral fins, filmed in the Sanctuary for the Marine Mammals of the Dominican Republic located on the Silver Bank. Each winter the Silver Bank is home to 3,000-5,000 North Atlantic humpback whales that gather there to court, mate and give birth. Lobtailing and slapping pectoral fins are two major surface social behaviors that they perform while there. Each winter, Each winter Conscious Breath Adventures guides a limited number of guests to the sanctaury where they can watch the whales from tenders, and also enter the water to swim with the whales eye to eye. To learn more visit www.ConsciousBreathAdventures.com.

description.original:
A humpback whale which was entangled in shark nets off Australia's Gold Coast has been freed by rescuers, local media reported. 

It's believed the 29-foot (9m) young humpback whale became entangled overnight on Tuesday. 

Sea World rescuers were able to free the whale quickly as it remained calm and weather conditions were favourable. 

The whale swam away freely and without any injuries, local media reported. 

Three whales have been caught in Queensland state shark nets so far this year.

description.original:
ID: 1546560

Footage from a breathtakingly close encounter with feasting humpback whales has been released. 

The clip shows the dozens of whales in pods and sea lines who come together to feed on small fish known as anchovies. 

Tour guide, Chase Dekker from Monterey Bay, California; said, "It’s usual to see feeding congregations at this time of year but each sighting is equally incredible. This group hung together for a couple of hours.

"I always think it’s amazing to see hundreds of animals working together to feed upon millions of fish. It’s a chaotic sight that never gets old and is a thrill to see for myself and all the guests that come out in the bay.

description.original: Today we watched three species of dolphins interact amongst each other and with Humpback Whales. The Pacific White Sided Dolphins and Northern Right Whale Dolphins displayed behaviors such as bow-riding, snout-riding on nearby Humpback Whales and porpoising out of the water! Risso's dolphins were also seen chasing some Pacific White Sided Dolphins. As we traveled with the different subgroups of dolphins, several Humpback whales exhibited surface behavior which was provoked by the snout-riding dolphins. The day was full of action! Book your trips today!

Humpback whales put the 'mega' in ocean megafauna. These incredible, graceful and gentle creatures make the long journey from the Antarctic to Mozambique's warm Indian Ocean every year, to breed and prepare their new calves for the long trip back.

This is a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to go on ocean safaris with marine scientists, as you collect data and support their research activities.

This shocked kiteboarder really did hit a hump in the road - as he rode right over a giant HUMPBACK WHALE

Having initially been gliding innocently across the water, Andrei Grigoriev's incredible footage then shows the exact moment he then collided with the large mammal.

Andrei's board skims right over the back of the rising whale, before the extreme sports enthusiast can be seen spreading his arms in utter amazement.

The moment was captured in the waters off Crissy Field Beach, California, USA, on June 18, 2017.

Andrei, 36, who lives in the Bay Area, said he had never even seen a whale before that moment, and though the footage may appear shocking, he never intended any harm to the animal; it was a complete accident.

description.original:
This was perhaps the coolest of our encounters (so far!) with humpback whales on the Great Barrier Reef during our 2018 research programme. Amazing what you can do with a GoPro camera!

Some humpback whale populations are doing great, others not so much. The population of humpback whales on the East Coast of Australia is increasing at about 11% per year! That's huge. Other populations in the South Pacific aren't doing so well. Among other things, we're trying to determine if the humpback whales seen on the east coast of Australia mix with those in the South Pacific and whether or not they should be managed as separate populations. Pretty fundamental and important stuff. 

If you'd like to be part of our research programme as a research assistant, visit our website www.blueplanetmarine.com. 

All data were collected under permits issued by the Australian Government and in accordance with our animal ethics approval.

Story:

In the middle of a California bay has captured the moment a massive whale unexpectedly jumped out of the water just metres away from two woman. 

Paddling with her daughter at Port San Luis on the weekend when a swarm of seagulls started diving into a nearby patch of water.

Moments later a humpback whale jumped out of the water right beside them.

The recent encounter is one of many in the Port San Luis area, which is why the harbour patrol are on high alert.


Australian regulations forbid coming within 100m of whales.

description.original:
Whale watchers out with Captain Dave's Dolphin and Whale Safari in Dana Point, California, got more than they bargained for when a friendly juvenile humpback whale repeatedly swam next to and under the whale watching catamaran. This is called a mugging. The humpback whale mugged the boat so much that the Captain couldn't leave! The muggings occurred throughout the day, on every trip, and other boats gathered nearby to watch this amazing spectacle.

Prior to 2014, Dana Point was well known for gray whale and blue whale watching. Southern California hosts the largest population of blue whales in the world during the summer months. Humpback whales were only seen occasionally, but within the last year sightings have increased exponentially, including a humpback that took up residence in the area for a couple of months last year. 

Like other baleen whales, humpback whales feed in colder waters and migrate to warmer climates for mating and calving. Humpbacks are seen off Southern California at sporadic times throughout the year when the whales are making their way up the coast in search of food or heading south to Mexico to mate and give birth. About 800 humpbacks are found off California in summer, mostly above Point Conception. 

Humpback whales can reach lengths of around 50 feet with females being slightly larger and they can weigh up to 40 tons. Their long pectoral flippers can be up to 15 feet in length. Humpbacks eat small fish and krill.

description.original:
Amazing whale encounter documents interaction between humans and playful Humpback Whales, sometimes referred to as "Dancers," in Tonga .
The unique video, shot by Rob Barrel, owner of the live-aboard dive boat NAI'A, shows Humpbacks approaching humans free-diving in Tonga, south of Fiji.  Highlights of the four-minute video clip show a whale spreading its pectoral fins as it mimicks diver John Tressman, another whale posing for author/photographer Paul Mila, and finally a humpback pirouetting for videographer Rob Barrel, and extending a pectoral fin attempting to make contact with him.

description.original:
Another short clip of a mother and her calf in the waters off the Great Barrier Reef, Australia. She was angry because her young had strayed too far.Visible tail slapping and blowhole exhalation. They come here to breed and give birth in warmer waters for several months before making the 2500 k journey back to Antarctica.

description.original:
We had watched this humpback whale from a distance and then did not see if for close to eight minutes when it unexpectedly surfaced not far from our kayaks and continued swimming toward us.

Whale watching guidelines dictate that we do not approach whales closer than 100 metres or purposefully put ourselves in their path of travel. In this instance we were surprised. So we stopped and enjoyed the privilege of seeing such a huge animals this close. More details on whale watching guidelines at http://www.kingfisher.ca/Be-Whale-Wise.pdf

Filmed by Scott Petersen on an Orca Waters Base Camp kayak tour with Kingfisher Wilderness Adventures http://www.kingfisher.ca

description.original:
A mother Humpback whale received the assistance from the Sea World Rescue Team to free her calf who was entangled in Shark Control netting in Australia. The calf was entangled off Coolangatta Beach, in the western Australian City of Gold Coast, accompanied by its mother who was trying to push it above water to breathe. Two patrol teams went out on rubber dinghies and cut the netting to free the calf.…

description.original:
#座頭鯨#HumpbackWhale#沒有

親愛的，有或沒有，都與幸福無關。

是的，有或沒有，對座頭鯨來說，都與幸福無關。對很多人來說，在我們的日常裡，有許多的人和事，好像和我們很有關，但其實認真的看來，又好像也無關。

真的，人生看起來，還真的沒什麼大道理，也不需要管那麼多。既然是這樣，面對人生，不如就實實在在的聽聽自己心裡的話，悲傷或喜樂，還不是這樣。想哭就哭吧然後再笑吧，沒有一個人或者一件事真的值得你那麼在乎的。

這就是我們的日常。座頭鯨寫/唱這歌，其實就是想要你懂得，你是幸福的。

座頭鯨 x Joseph N. x ErfixBahtiar
新加坡x 馬來西亞 x 印尼
跨國跨界跨文化的連結打造華語流行樂全新美學觀

是的，一個是被定位為遊走在主流與非主流之間的唱作人。一個是古典跨界的歌唱家。一個是生活在印尼的一個小鎮的YOUTUBER+獨立音樂人；一個長期在新加坡生活，一個長期在馬來西亞生活，另一個則是長期在印尼生活。這3個看起來，怎麼也不可能可以聯繫在一起的年輕人，為了【沒有】這首單曲，開始了一場跨國跨界跨文化的合作。

座頭鯨的作品，ERFIX BAHTIAR的編曲及吉他伴奏，JOSEPH N. 的製作。當初的想法，其實是希望跳脫大家對於目前市場上華語音樂熟悉的那個框架。所以寫流行歌的座頭鯨，碰上了受印尼土地文化薰陶的YOUTUBER+獨立音樂人ErfixBahtiar，再加上學古典聲樂的 Joseph N. 開始把自己生長的不同領域和國家對於音樂的認知，加入在這首歌裡頭。

主流和非主流日漸模糊的這個年代，【沒有】這首歌，就是希望能讓大家拋開既定的，聽慣了的華語流行歌曲及西洋歌曲的框架，嘗試打造一個跨國跨界跨文化的華語流行樂全新美學觀。

description.original:
During our whale watching safari today, our drone operator Domenic filmed this exciting scene of a baby Humpback Whale throwing a temper tantrum! The calf had been trying to nurse, and when mom doesn't give the calf enough, the little one gets frustrated. The calf lifts the entire lower half of its body and tail out of the water and lands right on top of mom. This behavior is known as a peduncle throw.


*****

description.original: Source: https://anglers-adventures.com/ - While fishing with Anglers Adventures of Ketchikan, Alaska on the F/V Sierra Dawn captain Brian Ringeisen spotted the telltale signs of humpback whales about to execute one of the most interesting feeding rituals of whales in the world. Known as Bubble Net Feeding, or Bubble Feeding locally, the whales find large schools of herring and begin swimming circles below them while blowing bubbles to push the fish closer and closer together, then all at once come together at the surface with their mouths open swallowing hundreds of fish at a time.

description.original:
While drifting in the Pacific Ocean in hopes of landing some dinner we crossed paths with a mother and baby humpback whale. The baby was very curious and playful while the mother hovered 20m below with an occasional surface to breath. After this initial accent we all clipped our spearguns to a float and watched as the baby played on the surface. This went on for 30 minutes around us, we were very conscious to keep a safe and respectful distance between these magnificent mammals and us. It was a dream come true! Heres a sneak peak of the footage, you might be able to tell I was a little stoked ;)

description.original:
Captain Dave Anderson of Capt. Dave's Dolphin and Whale Safari in Dana Point, California, has recently filmed and edited a brand new video that contains never-before-seen footage of a mother and calf humpback whale being escorted by a sea lion. The mother and calf pair has been staying in the Dana Point area for a week now. "At first I thought the sea lion was a dolphin, but was surprised to discover that it was, in fact, a sea lion bow-riding on the the mother's forward thrust.  As we watched the mother and calf we saw another startling behavior that I had never seen before.  The mother actually extends her left pectoral flipper towards the calf for several minutes...and then, just before a dive, touches the calf's chin, as if to lift it's head or blow hole out of the water to exhale before diving. I've never seen anything like it. It's like a human mother who is holding her child's hand. Without the drone's perspective, we would not have been able to see this interaction between the mother and calf. It was just beautiful and I was really moved to see the mother do this."
  
According to N.O.A.A. Southern California has the greatest density of dolphins in the world. We have pods up to 10,000 strong stretched out for miles like the wildebeests of Africa. Over 400,000 common dolphin alone. We also have the largest concentration of blue whales on earth.

Entanglement in fishing gear takes the lives of nearly 1,000 dolphins and whales ever day around the world. Captain Dave formed Orange County's first whale disentanglement group in 2008 and has been involved in disentangling several whales, including a gray whale named Lily, whose disentanglement in Dana Point Harbor made national headlines. He authored the award-winning book, "Lily, A Gray Whale's Odyssey", which won eight awards in 2013.

Special Note From Captain Dave:

Attention any would be whale videographers: please only attempt this if you are extremely familiar with whale behavior as it is illegal to do anything that causes the whales to change their normal behavior with big fines- and the authorities do watch YouTube. Different areas have different laws on approaching whales. I am a whale watch captain with nearly 20 years of experience. All laws were obeyed by us during filming. The Mom and calf as you can see in the film were completely undisturbed by the small drone. NOAA is currently reviewing drones and may create laws or guidelines for using them around whales.

Fully licensed music by David Hollandsworth http://davidhollandsworth.com/

Video footage is copyright David Anderson/DolphinSafari.com and may not be used without permission.

description.original:
Federal officials have declared an “unusual mortality event” after finding a high number of dead whales washing ashore on the East coast. Scientists are investigating the cause, which could provide greater insight into larger environmental issues.
On Wednesday, the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) Marine Fisheries issued a press release, declaring an “unusual mortality event” when an abnormally high number of marine mammals were found dead for unknown reasons. There have been 62 such events designated since 1991, when the program was established.

This VR underwater snorkel is with Humpback Whales, a Mother & new born Calf in the Pacific Tonga.

The Calf is estimated at 3-4 wks old.

Watch the amazing bond between a mother and child,
Watch the calf mimic mum as it learns it way in this big new world.
  
They come very close, look out for the wave good bye!!!

Please note that swimming with these gentle giants happen under the guide of licensed operators.

Pleas always respect wildlife.

description.original:
For eons Humpback Whales have made their way to the Silver Bank of the Dominican Republic for mating and calving.   If all things go right, Cindy and I will be on the Silver Bank to film and document these gentle giants with  Tom Conlin of Aquatic Adventures. 
The Aquatic Adventures Team collectively has 386 weeks of know-how in approaching, working and interacting with humpback whales of the Silver Bank. 
A soft-in-water encounter is not scuba diving, nor is it aggressive swimming or free diving. It is passive, non-aggressive floating at the surface, in mask, fins and snorkel, allowing the whale to develop an interest in humans. It is finding a cooperative, tolerant and/or curious whale and meeting that whale in the water, calmly and peacefully, permitting a rare and treasured encounter between human and cetacean. Through 20 years of experience these methods have been proved to generate the best, closest and most numerous encounters. © Tom Conlin

description.original: Sunday morning was anything but ordinary. A beautiful morning and glassy waters were the stage to an amazing natural spectacle. After sailing for a while, we were coming back to Santa Cruz harbor and found a large aggregation of marine life feeding on fish. Sea birds, sea lions, harbor seals, dolphins and a humpback whale were the predators. After observing the whale surfacing to breathe several times, we decided to head out. Little did we know that we will see the whale one more time except, this time it came out with its mouth opened and barely missing a paddle boarder who was coming out of the harbor. We could not believe it! He escaped danger twice by centimeters... Fortunately he is ok and we got the action on video!

description.original:
Tom Mustill
Regno Unito | 2019 | 59’

Il 12 Settembre 2015 a Monterey Bay, California, una megattera di 30 chili balzò fuori dall’acqua e ricadde proprio sul kayak di Tom Mustill e dell’amica Charlotte Kinloch. Incredibilmente entrambi sopravvissero. Tom, documentarista per professione, non smise però di pensare all’incidente che avrebbe potuto ucciderlo, chiedendosi se l’animale volesse intenzionalmente far loro del male.
Per far luce sull’accaduto, Tom ritorna in California nel 2018, intervistando studiosi e protagonisti di esperienze da brividi, simili alla sua. Questi incontri sollevano interrogativi ancor più profondi, non solo in relazione all’accaduto. Tom si interroga sul rapporto fra l’uomo e i cetacei, e sul futuro di questi animali destinati a convivere con l’uomo.

description.original:
A humpback whale is filmed breaching in British Gibraltar territorial waters on January 7, 2016.

The whale was spotted by HM Customs (Gibraltar) officers on board HMC Seeker approximately three miles south of Europa Point at around 0900hrs.

"We were on a routine patrol of BGTW when we spotted some splashes in the distance which we initially thought was a rigid-hulled inflatable boat but it turned out to be a whale," said Customs officer Richard Lavagna, who filmed the whale.
title.original: Humpback whale breaching off Gibraltar

description.original:
A humpback whale has been freed from a shark net off the coast of Australia's Noosa Head's Main Beach. Officials say the mammal was probably trapped overnight but still breathing when they reached it. Rescuers managed to cut through the net that had trapped the adult male whale and allow it to swim away.

Humpback whales migrate north from the Antarctic to the warmer waters off Australia's coast from June to November. Report by Ashley Fudge.

description.original:
Swimming with Orcas and Humpback Whales in the fjords of northern Norway. Filmed by Vera, Rolf and Martin.

"There is no danger in swimming with orcas, except for the danger of falling in love with these intelligent, charismatic and mysterious creatures. The more time I spend with them above and below the water, the more empathy I feel for the challenges they face. Toxic accumulation of substances like PCBs that cause high mortality, captivity for entertainment, starvation due to overfishing, and even the fact that in some countries they are still hunted for food, not to mention a rapidly changing ocean chemistry! The Great Orca Fjords of Norway are a sanctuary for these animals; let's keep oil exploitation out of these beautiful fjords!" – Cristina Mittermeier
title.original: Swimming with Orcas and Humpback Whales

description.original:
Clips of Humback Whales visiting Port San Luis. Shot from Harford Pier with Avila Beach in the background.  This is the first time these gentle giants have been in the bay and right at the pier.  The large birds are California Brown Pelicans and the Harbor Seals are also having a great time chowing down on oddles of bait fish too.  Some dolphins are also jumping around from time to time in the bay and also along the Pismo Beach coast.

The whales are on their normal migration from more Northern water to warm Southern waters for the Winter.  They are usually at least a mile off shore, but this year some have decided to come within a few hundred feet of shore.  It's a great show.

description.original:
Video from a Baltimore Sea Safari whale watching boat trip off Baltimore in West Cork, Ireland - watching Humpback whales bubble net feeding on sprats. Humpback whales have developed an unusual technique for feeding on shoals of fish, they drop deep in the water and swim around in a circle blowing bubbles. the circle of bubbles rise slowly to the surface, trapping fish in the center of the bubbles (like a curtain of bubbles), then they rise through the center of the ring with their huge mouths open scooping up all the fish contained within the ring. They usually settle on the surface of the water for a few seconds to force the water out through their baleen plates, and  to swallow the fish, before often repeating the process. This is an adult and a sub adult working together.
Baltimore Sea Safari operate daily coastal sightseeing boat trips with whale, dolphin and wildlife watching from Baltimore in County Cork.

description.original:
Drone footage of a great white shark and humpback whales at the Kermadec Islands, NZ's northern most territory. 
It was just announced that the Kermadec region will become one of the world's largest Marine Sanctuary's in 2016. The sanctuary will be about 2 times the size of NZ's land mass. 
We expected to see lots of humpback whales on their migration south to their feeding grounds in Antarctica on this scientific expedition - we didn't expect to bump into any great white sharks! One of the GWS's has been positively identified as a shark that was tagged in 2011 at Stewart Island (about 2500km south). 

Read about this scientific expedition here:

http://kermadec.aucklandmuseum.com/about-expedition/2015-the-great-humpback-whale-trail/

Check out our website:  www.youngoceanexplorers.com

description.original: Swimming with humpback whales with Bluewater Explorer off Eua Island, Tonga. This was shot with a GoPro and the sound is as it was on the day - including my ohhhh's and ahhh's as I saw them for the first time.  This experience was a life changing one and I am so honoured that these beautiful whales were so trusting and wanted to interact with us. We swam with many different whales and each time was different and always on their terms.  If they wanted to play, they stayed. If they didn't, they swam off. What is so amazing to me is that they are so large yet so gentle and you can see how close they got to me but I always felt safe. There was one moment that baby swims past very closely, followed by Mum and Mum turns around to face me, decides that I must be okay and then rolls onto her back - within inches of me!! You can see me trying to move backwards out of their way but I needn't have done that as they know exactly where they are and where I was. Amazing experience and one that will stay with me forever!
title.original: Swimming with Humpback Whales Tonga 2018

description.original:
Please share & subscribe! YOU MIGHT NEVER PASS THIS WAY AGAIN....   PLEASE READ THIS WHOLE DESCRIPTION ! IMPORTANT INFO INCLUDED BEFORE SWIMMING WITH WHALES.

Working on other videos of swimming with humpback whales in Neiafu Vava'u Kingdom of Tonga. 

What an amazing time it is of swimming in the Pacific Ocean alongside the humpback whales as they come to Vava'u to give birth to their calf. They swim past the island of Hunga and go off toward Fiji and other South Pacific Ocean islands along with the orca, humpback, beluga and dolphin. 

We could not only swim with the whales but we were also just able to sit and whale watch from the boat. My friend Jimmy was not able to get in the water so he was fine simply whale watching from above the water without snorkeling with the whales. I shot lots of amazing video too! Whales coming up for air and splashing on their side, and going below the surface with fins up and whale tails above the water. We must have seen about 30-40 whales on a chartered boat we hired, it was a fast jet boat by Vaka Vave Charters. It was fantastic!

There are only a few places in the world where you can swim with giant whales of this earth! Vava'u Kingdom of Tonga is one, and down in Sri Lanka you can snorkel and swim with giant blue whale. But that's about it. I have heard that down in Tahiti you can swim with the humpbacks also, but i heard that it is really expensive... here in Tonga and Sri Lanka it is still not crowded and very cheap to swim with the whales, BUT, it might not be for long... AND it might not be legal for long too... ;) They may decide to one day ban it. Better do it before you don't ever get the chance to do it. :) Ya' know, carpe diem and all that stuff! ... ;) 

In Tonga, there are people who schedule swimming with the whales as THE main thing they do when the come to the South Pacific islands! Every single day they go snorkeling and diving with the whales. It is all they do! :) I met two people on the flights to Fiji and that was what they did for 8 days. WOAAH! :)

On our tour we went with an amazing charter company called Vaka Vave Charter. You will find Diane and Izzy and the whole crew and blast to go with! REALLY you won't be disappointed!!!!!  The whales will be quite intrigued by you being there and as you can see they will possibly swim to you. 

BUT DO NOT SWIM AT (TOWARDS) THEM AND BY ALL MEAN DO NOT DO NOT TOUCH THEM!!!!!! THIS WILL GET YOU TAKEN AWAY FROM THEM QUICKLY!!!  WHALES ARE VERY STRONG AND IF THEY HIT YOU WITH THEIR TAIL OR FIN YOU CAN GET HURT BY THEM. THEY DONT MEAN TO BUT YOU ARE IN THEIR TERRITORY. SO BACK AWAY AND WATCH OUT!!!!

description.original:
Occurred on June 8, 2019 / Santa Barbara, California, USA

We spotted multiple humpback whales and thousands of common dolphins. Right as we were about to head into the dock, my best friend Kristin spotted a humpback whale breaching in the distance. Although we knew the whale would probably stop breaching before we got to it, Captain Dave and the rest of our crew went there anyways. The whale stopped breaching but “mugged” our boat. It made several close passes, slapped its pectoral fins on the surface, and hung out next to our boat for about an hour.

This is the stunning moment a group of divers get up-close-and-personal with a pair of curious humpback whales. 

Divers from whale swimming tour company Coral Bay Ecotour were out diving with some clients in the Ningaloo Reef, Western Australia, when they had a once-in-a-lifetime encounter with two huge humpback whales. 

Coral Bay’s in-house drone pilot, Dan Spillane, 30, filmed the amazing birds-eye footage as the two giants swam in a circle around the group of stunned divers on July 15. 

Dan said: “We film humpbacks every day, and normally they just swim past the divers rather than stopping to check them out.

description.original:
From a whale watch in January 2018 off the west coast of Maui.

A few humpback whales.  One of the whales trumpets, then a few of the sky-hopped (where the whale sticks it's head out of the water, almost like they are checking us out).

I believe orcas are more well known for sky-hopping, though many whales have this behavior.  This was the first time I had ever seen it from the humpbacks on a whale watch.
title.original: Skyhopping humpback whales

description.original:
Today was one of the absolute best whale watching experiences of my life. It's been almost two full years since I've seen surface active humpback whales, and the wait was sure worth it. Hours of breaching, mugging, and pec slapping from at least 20 different humpback whales. The highlight was a single whale that literally did at least 100 pec slaps right next to the boat! Thank you to Pacific Offshore Expeditions and Captain Ryan Lawler for making today happen!

Please like, subscribe, and share!

description.original:
While I was on a whale-watching trip out of Akureyri, Iceland in late June of 2019, a humpback whale approached our boat and began slapping his tail forcefully on the water. You can see the dramatic behavior in this video. (My apologies for the distracting wind noise — I was not equipped at the time with an external mic and windscreen.)

This may look like the whale is saying, "Get the hell out of here!" But research suggests this common behavior is a form of close-range communication with other whales. 

Among a number of findings, the research, led by Ailbhe Kavanagh at the University of Queensland in Gatton, Australia, showed that just before new whales joined up, or an existing group split up, repetitive tail and pectoral-fin slapping suddenly increased.

Don't humpbacks communicate by "singing" with a host of vocalized sounds? Indeed, they do. But the research also showed that both breaching — when whales hurl themselves out of the water and come crashing back down — and fin-slapping increased when it was windy. One possible reason: In windy conditions, vocal sounds could be less audible, prompting whales to switch to their own form of Morse code.

The study was published in 2016 in the journal Marine Mammal Science: https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/mms.12374

description.original:
Muscat: Rescue teams are currently being scrambled to rescue a rare Arabian Sea humpback whale, which has become entangled in a fishing net off the coast of Muscat.

The whale, which was sighted about 65km from the shore, is one of just 100 individuals of the Arabian Sea humpback whale population, which has been classified as endangered on the International Union for Conservation of Nature’s Red List, a catalogue of animals facing extinction.



A joint statement from the Environmental Society of Oman (ESO) and Oman Sail was released just minutes after the whale had been discovered.

“Inform all vessels to look for an endangered humpback whale that is entangled in a fishing net,” said Assim Al Saqri, acting head of communications for Oman Sail. “Its last known position was 65km east off Muscat’s coast on Friday, November 11, and is presumed to be slowly swimming southwards.

“This whale is one out of only 100 individuals of the Arabian Sea humpback whale population, which are classified as endangered on the IUCN Red List, so every whale counts!” he added.

Residents who sight the whale are requested to note the time, location and direction of the whale’s travel and immediately report it to the Ministry of Environment and Climate Affairs’ (MECA) 24-hour wildlife emergency hotline, on 24696333, or inform the ESO on 99855108, or through social media, and if possible, the Royal Oman Police coastguard as well.

“If possible please take photographs of the sighting but maintain a safe distance of 100m from the distressed whale,” added Al Saqri. “DO NOT ATTEMPT to release it yourself as it’s a highly dangerous situation! A response team from MECA, who are specially trained, will mobilise to respond to any reports of the whale to disentangle it.”

description.original: In 2011, a humpback whale chose our boat to investigate and explore. It was such an exciting experience for the 4 of us aboard. We'd been watching a breaching whale from a safe and legal distance, when the 2 whales surprised us by coming near our boat. Our motor was off and we were drifting quietly at the time. The more active of the two swam away while this one stayed and swam around and under our boat for over 30 minutes. It was incredible! This happened in the waters near Coffman Cove, Alaska on Prince of Wales Island. We were on the Inside Passage on a beautiful summer day in a 24 ft. Hewescraft. I still am in awe of the experience! I have more videos of the encounter and lots of photos. It was AMAZING!!!!
title.original: Humpback Whale Visits our Boat in SE Alaska!!!

description.original: In order to catch the fish they prey on, humpback whales will circle a school of fish, blowing bubbles.  The fish won't swim through the wall of bubbles, so the whale will swim in smaller and smaller circles, corralling them in a vertical column of bubbles.  The whale will then swim up through the center of the column with its mouth open to swallow the fish.  One of the whales did this right next to the boat.  She started to create another bubble column (that's what this video is) but abandoned it.  The guide said that happens sometimes if they end up too close to the boat.  So this is just a bubble column.  Then you can see the whale a few seconds later swimming away.
title.original: Humpback whale, feeding bubbles

description.original:
A playful humpback whale put on a rare show for onlookers breaching more than 30 TIMES. The incredible scenes were also captured in crystal-clear footage by staff at California-based Monterey Bay Whale Watch, who shot the energetic mammal against a misty backdrop. Looking like something out of a movie, the whale continued to breach, over and over again - much to the delight of those watching. Nancy Black, a marine biologist and owner of Monterey Bay Whale Watch, said that in her 30 years of studying whales, she has only seen the creatures breach this many time on a few occasions.

description.original:
MONTEREY BAY -- A couple of kayakers in California have a big new friend -- a 40-foot whale to be exact. They shared a story that is hard to believe. Thankfully, a photo confirms it all, An 80,000-pound Humpback whale swam right next to one of the kayakers in Monterey Bay while her shocked friend captured the moment. "When I took the photo I was really scared, well, I didn't know what was going to happen to Karen. When I got back to land, I realized that was probably the best photo I've ever seen," the kayaker said.
Experts say the whales are just out looking for lunch; particularly the anchovies in Monterey Bay's submarine canyon.
title.original: Kayaker Encounters 80000 Pound 'Humpback Whale' in Monterey Bay - Karen Hatch

An 40ft humpbackwhale seemsed to be stuck in a crab trap. When a 12ft boat stops a 100 meter to check on the whale, it turns out that whale is not stuck and now the whale checks out the boat!! This is extremely rare behaviour and should not be taken as an encouragement to approach whales. As per the recommendations from DFO in a zone of 400 meter from a whale boaters should slow down and keep a sharp lookout. If the whale turn up at 100 meters or less go to neutral and or cut your engine!
title.original: humpback whale eye to eye

description.original:
The humpback whale (Megaptera novaeangliae) is a species of baleen whale. 

One of the larger rorqual species, adults range in length from 12-16 metres (39-52 ft) and weigh approximately 36,000 kilograms (79,000 lb). The humpback has a distinctive body shape, with unusually long pectoral fins and a knobbly head. 

Found in oceans and seas around the world, humpback whales typically migrate up to 25,000 kilometres (16,000 mi) each year. Humpbacks feed only in summer, in polar waters, and migrate to tropical or sub-tropicalwaters to breed and give birth in the winter.

Like other large whales, the humpback was and is a target for the whaling industry. Due to over-hunting, its population fell by an estimated 90% before a whaling moratorium was introduced in 1966.

Stocks have since partially recovered; however, entanglement in fishing gear, collisions with ships, and noise pollution also remain concerns

There are at least 80,000 humpback whales worldwide. Once hunted to the brink of extinction, humpbacks are now sought by whale-watchers, particularly off parts of Australia, New Zealand, South America, Canada, and the United States.
title.original: Humpback whale: Acrobatic animal

description.original:
記得,初學自由潛水時,最大的夢想就是跟大翅鯨共遊~
很幸運的,我實現了這個願望!
這趟旅程學到了很多~
在7-9月南極的大翅鯨會跑到TONG來繁殖.哺育幼鯨.所以最常見到的為母子對,也就是媽媽帶寶寶.
每天,我們出海尋找噴氣點,有時候幸運出海不到一小時就看見"碰",一團煙霧,有時船上坐到睡著水面還是風平浪靜,一切憑運氣{幸好我們出海8天都有見著}尋找到大翅鯨之後,還不急著跳水,先觀察是否適合下水或是牠是一直在跑的,常常船邊一等就是一個小時,都曬黑了!!哈哈~~
碰見大翅鯨在海裡型態多為{母子對}.ESCORT{護衛鯨}.SINGER{唱歌}.HEAT RUN{多隻一起衝刺,翻轉,游動為最精采},幾天下來,我們遇見的有最常見的MOM&CALFSINGER這一次我們只聽見遠方傳來聲音,沒有被聲波震到! 還有一次HEAT RUN在海面看見5隻,這時船長要丟人丟的準,跳水/上船手腳要快才追得上,可惜那一次我們一跳HEATRUN分開了!!燈愣...哈哈~不過最爽就是有一跳的母子對讓我們跟了至少一小時,追的我隔天都要鐵腿..每一次寶寶上來換氣我就會專注地拍寶寶,瞬間媽媽俯衝上來,那簡直跟大卡車要撞上來一樣,開始忙著找逃生路線,最後應該是大翅鯨媽媽在閃我們,一個MOVE就過去了!!太鯨采了!
人生有幾次能有這樣的經驗,你說是吧!?{怎麼有種老人口吻}
最後一晚,民宿主人宴慶我們各國的追鯨部隊,哈哈~PARTY!!派對有豐盛的食物,還有還有,當地有種加了某種植物的酒叫作KAVA,看起來像DIRTY FLOOR WATER,他們說喝了會一杯接一杯~最後會有種迷幻感,但我喝了8碗,只有舌頭麻一下就無感哩!哈~派對裡見到大家不一樣的一面,平常看起來靦腆的潛導,跳起舞來也是很會呢!!!
旅程總要畫上句點,期待下一次的海洋奇遇.
去挪威看虎鯨及大翅鯨覓食吧!!

description.original:
A woman vacationing on Mexico's Sea of Cortez shows the shocking moment a humpback whale breached onto a fishing boat.
Gillian Panasewicz, who is from Arizona, captured a series of stunning pictures showing the massive mammal coming up for air right as a boat was overhead.
Thankfully, neither the whale nor those on the boat were injured.
Canada's Globe and Mail reports that Panasewicz was vacationing in the country and captured the whale breaching from a nearby vessel. 
She captured several other stunning images, one of the whale nearly capsizing a small Mexican fishing boat.
Humpbacks are among the most easily recognised whales because of their long flippers.
They get their name from the hump under the dorsal fin, which is particularly noticeable when the mammal arches its back to dive.
The humpback can reach a maximum length of 15-18 meters and weigh up to 40 tons.
During the peak of the whaling industry's activities in the 1960s and 70s, the numbers of humpbacks fell dramatically, and although they are now protected, they are still considered a vulnerable species by marine environmentalists.
title.original: The incredible moment a humpback whale tips up a motor boat

Boaters sailing around Cape Henry, Virginia, were left stunned and in awe when they witnessed a humpback whale taking a giant leap nearby on February 19.

This video shows a humpback whale swimming near a boat before making a splash to spectators’ delight. The leap even drenched a few people, according to local reports.

Jeff Brown, who was fortunate enough to capture the once-in-a-lifetime experience on camera, said it was their "fourth trip this year to Cape Henry whale watching, but none [of them] compared to this.”
title.original: Humpback Whale Takes a Giant Leap, Stuns Boaters Off Cape Henry

description.original:
www.whalesbermuda.com 
Every once in a while while conducting my research I have a close encounter in the water with humpbacks. These encounters are always on the whales' terms. This unedited 7-minute clip reveals how they approached me while I am completely passive. Over time they became increasingly curious and relaxed with my presence. This encounter with a pair of dancers was the better part of three hours and as is apparent in the video they often approached headfirst within 3-4 feet of me, sticking their heads out of the water, rolling over onto their backs. The encounter with two adult humpback whales in the middle of the ocean where the water was as clear as a swimming pool is unique.
These images were taken under a Protected Species Licence for Scientific Research Activities Licence no. 14-04-11-3 issued by the Government of Bermuda, Department of Conservation Services

description.original:
A glimpse under the water while on tour in Tonga with Swimming with Gentle Giants. We travel to these pristine waters for the chance to snorkel with humpback whales, with a backdrop of tropical islands, caves and coral reef. 

With over 17 years experience swimming with humpback whales in Tonga, photographer Scott Portelli captures incredible moments with mothers and calves, unique behaviours and the beauty of this incredible marine environment. 

Join a tour to experience this for yourself at: 
http://swimmingwithgentlegiants.com/


About Scott Portelli: 
"I have travelled the world extensively photographing in some of the most remote destinations, including the Arctic, Antarctica, Galapagos, Azores, Africa and the South Pacific. As a wildlife photographer I have spent hundreds of days in pursuit of different wildlife and been privileged to be up close and personal with many creatures. 

I have spent the last decade working with Humpback whales photographing and filming their behaviour above and below the waves. I have received a number of internationally acclaimed awards with works appearing in a multitude of magazines and publications including BBC’s ‘Life’ series book and various documentaries on Australian and New Zealand Television. I have a passion for the ocean and an affinity with whales and cetaceans."

See more of Scott's work:

description.original: On yesterday's 8am whale watching trip, we had blue skies and we watched a group of several Humpback Whales feeding with California Sea Lions. They fed below the surface and spent a lot of time at the surface before fluking up and repeating the cycle, making for great looks. Several pairs of Humpback Whales curiously approached the boat while we were neutral! They surfaced right next to the boat giving us an amazing perspective of how large they really are.
title.original: Humpback Whale Feeding Frenzy and Friendly Behavior

Two Humpback whales surfacing resting beside Baltimore Sea Safari. Baltimore Sea Safari were operating whale and dolphin watching boat trip along the Wild Atlantic Way from Baltimore in West Cork, Ireland.

We didn't chase these whales - they surfaced close to us and approached us, prior to 'resting' and then took off.

description.original:
Humpback Whales Close Encounter A close encounter with two incredible humpback whales.

Found in oceans and seas around the world, humpback whales typically migrate up to 25,000 km  (16,000 mi) each year.
Humpbacks feed in polar waters, and migrate to tropical or subtropical waters to breed and give birth when they
fast and live off their fat reserves. Their diet consists mostly of krill and small fish. Humpbacks have a diverse repertoire of feeding methods, including the bubble net technique.

Like other large whales, the humpback was a target for the whaling
industry. Once hunted to the brink of extinction, its population 
fell by an estimated 90% before a 1966 moratorium. While stocks have partially recovered, entanglement in fishing gear, collisions with ships and noise pollution continue to impact the population of 80,000.

Don't approach the wildlife, they said. All good and well, until the wildlife came to us. And believe me, a humpback up close is a sight you won't soon forget. 

Matt Brown, base commander of Rothera research station on the Antarctic peninsula, was showing us around Ryder Bay, when he suddenly spotted a young humpback whale in the distance. First we admired her from afar, but later she got closer. And closer. Until she surfaced right in front us. 

Footage by Margot Custers.
