description.original:
During a March 2019 expedition in Raja Ampat, Indonesia we encountered these two playful Bryde’s whales and watched them surface and rest for more than an hour. At one point the whales surfaced within feet of the bow! Luckily, our accompanying researchers from Planet Deep had their new Mavic Pro 2 (drone) high above to capture this footage.

This encounter took place during a 12-day private expedition aboard the luxurious El Aleph organized by Oceanic Society in partnership with Planet Deep for a group of friends from the United States. Beyond daily snorkeling, our expedition had an onboard whale expert. A portion of our days is spent looking for, identifying, and monitoring cetaceans to help better understand how whales use the waterways within Raja Ampat.

For upcoming travel opportunities aboard El Aleph on Raja Ampat, see https://www.oceanicsociety.org/expeditions/banda-sea-reefs-blue-whales-and-hammerhead-sharks--1965

Video captured by Planet Deep / Johannes Hennicke.
title.original: Bryde's whales in Raja Ampat, Indonesia - Oceanic Society expedition

The glory of the world’s oceans could be restored within a generation, according to a major new scientific review. It reports rebounding sea life, from humpback whales off Australia to elephant seals in the US and green turtles in Japan. Through rampant overfishing, pollution and coastal destruction, humanity has inflicted severe damage on the oceans and its inhabitants for centuries. But conservation successes, while still isolated, demonstrate the remarkable resilience of the seas. The scientists say there is now the knowledge to create an ocean renaissance for wildlife by 2050 and with it bolster the services that the world’s people rely on, from food to coastal protection to climate stability. The measures needed, including protecting large swathes of ocean, sustainable fishing and pollution controls, would cost billions of dollars a year, the scientists say, but would bring benefits 10 times as high. However, the escalating climate crisis must also be tackled to protect the oceans from acidification, loss of oxygen and the devastation of coral reefs. The good news, the scientists say, is a growing awareness of the ability of oceans and coastal habitats such as mangroves and salt marshes to rapidly soak up carbon dioxide and bolster shorelines against rising sea levels.“We have a narrow window of opportunity to deliver a healthy ocean to our grandchildren, and we have the knowledge and tools to do so,” said Prof Carlos Duarte, of King Abdullah University of Science and Technology in Saudi Arabia, who led the review. “Failing to embrace this challenge, and in so doing condemning our grandchildren to a broken ocean unable to support good livelihoods is not an option.”Prof Callum Roberts, at the University of York, one of the review’s international team, said: “Overfishing and climate change are tightening their grip, but there is hope in the science of restoration.“One of the overarching messages of the review is, if you stop killing sea life and protect it, then it does come back. We can turn the oceans around and we know it makes sense economically, for human wellbeing and, of course, for the environment.”The review, published in the journal Nature, found that global fishing is slowly becoming more sustainable and the destruction of habitats such as seagrass meadows and mangroves is almost at a halt. In places from Tampa Bay, Florida to the Philippines, the habitats are being restored. Among the success stories are humpback whales that migrate from Antarctica to eastern Australia, whose populations have surged from a few hundred animals in 1968, before whaling was banned, to more than 40,000 today. Sea otters in western Canada have risen from just dozens in 1980 to thousands now. In the Baltic Sea, both grey seal and cormorant populations are soaring.“We’re beginning to appreciate the value of what we’re losing and not just in terms of intrinsic beauty of the wildlife but in terms of protecting our livelihoods and societies from bad things

description.original:
It was late in the season and the winds were iffy in the far North of KwaZulu-Natal. The windows for quality surf were becoming fewer and even more far between. We'd spent days and nights at Zag HQ, hunkered over our computers analysing the patterns on Windy. Digger, our guide and masterful boat captain was getting fidgety. Maybe we'd have to delay the long-held plans to explore this hidden corner of coast for some undefined future date...

We've been scoping the region for a few years already. The main attraction being that you can blitz up from Durban smash two days of truly perfect tropical surf and be back in the office with a smile on your face, salt in your ears and a bit of sunblock still on your nose. Carrying stiff shoulders and a bit of fatigue into the rest of your week. 

Finally, the window opened, just a crack, spring lows in the morning, two days of gentle winds, mainly in an offshore direction and most importantly, a pumping East Swell. Two frothing surfers in Davey van Zyl and Saxton Randall, ready to drop everything in a 'surfer's minute' and hit the road, a vehicle, a tank full of petrol and a videographer in the form of Michael Veltman. We made the call in the morning, finally managed to collar the surfers (we had to wait for Davey to come back from a night training flight before we could bail), then shop for supplies, and we finally made the open road by 10pm. 

A few short few hours of kip, then up at 5 to greet the day on the beach, pile all the gear into Digger's rubber duck and weave through the stiff lines on the boat launch and out into the open sea. This stretch of coast is wild, dolphins are the locals but there are plenty of humpback whales, turtles and signs of gamefish everywhere.

And the waves... well there were some of those. Watch the full edit below for proof. And the good news is... this swell wasn't even perfect. A little too straight to properly wrap around and rumble through the Cove. Which can only mean one thing... We'll be back to explore this amazing region at the next golden opportunity. 

Now sit back, relax and enjoy Zag's almost perfectly executed strike mission to Digger's Cove!


*Big thanks to VANS for pulling the trigger with us to make it happen.
title.original: ZagTV pres. 'Diggers Cove"

description.original:
Video tratando temas MGTOW sobre dinámica social. Conceptos básicos de la teoría Red Pill. Hipergamia, regla de Pareto (80/20), hibristofilia, estrategias sexuales, cuello de botella reproductivo, iniciativa y roles de género, el muro. Respuesta a Zósimo. 
Mujeres consideran más atractivos a los hombres rodeados de mujeres:
Scofield, J. E., Kostic, B., & Buchanan, E. M. (2020). “How the Presence of Others Affects Desirability Judgments in Heterosexual and Homosexual Participants”. Archives of Sexual Behavior, 49(2): p.623-633.
Estudios de C. Rudder (okCupid):
Rudder, C. (2014). Dataclismo. Aguilar. ISBN: 9788403515086.
Rudder, C. (2009). “Your Looks and Your Inbox”. OkTrends. https://www.gwern.net/docs/psychology/okcupid/yourlooksandyourinbox.html Consulta: 16 marzo 2020.
Estudio de Tinder de Medium:
https://medium.com/@worstonlinedater/tinder-experiments-ii-guys-unless-you-are-really-hot-you-are-probably-better-off-not-wasting-your-2ddf370a6e9a
Hibristofilia:
Provenzano, D. A., Dane, A. V., Farrell, A. H., Marini, Z. A., & Volk, A. A. (2018). “Do bullies have more sex? The role of personality”. Evolutionary Psychological Science, 4(3), p.221-232.
Iniciativa y poder de selección sexual:
Clark, R. D., & Hatfield, E. (1989). “Gender differences in receptivity to sexual offers”. Journal of Psychology & Human Sexuality, 2(1): p.39-55.
Finkel, E. J., & Eastwick, P. W. (2009). “Arbitrary social norms influence sex differences in romantic selectivity”. Psychological Science, 20(10): p.1290-1295.
Mills, M. (2011). “Why Don’t Women Ask Men Out on First Dates?”. Psychology Today. 
Kerr, S. (2018). “The Dating Game”. SSRN 2869449.
Matches y mensajes recibidos con el tiempo:
Tyson, G., Perta, V. C., Haddadi, H., & Seto, M. C. (2016). “A first look at user activity on tinder”. IEEE/ACM International Conference on Advances in Social Networks Analysis and Mining (ASONAM): p. 461-466. 
La hipergamia no cambia con las culturas:
Zhang, L., Lee, A. J., DeBruine, L. M., & Jones, B. C. (2019). “Are sex differences in preferences for physical attractiveness and good earning capacity in potential mates smaller in countries with greater gender equality?”. Evolutionary Psychology, 17(2).
Buss, D. M. (1989). “Sex differences in human mate preferences: Evolutionary hypotheses tested in 37 cultures”. Journal of Behavioral and brain sciences, 12 (1): p.1-14.
Hipergamia en otros mamíferos:
Wroblewski, E. E., Murray, C. M., Keele, B. F., Schumacher-Stankey, J. C., Hahn, B. H., & Pusey, A. E. (2009). “Male dominance rank and reproductive success in chimpanzees, Pan troglodytes schweinfurthii”. Animal Behaviour, 77(4): p.873-885.
Cerchio, S., Jacobsen, J. K., Cholewiak, D. M., Falcone, E. A., & Merriwether, D. A. (2005). “Paternity in humpback whales, Megaptera novaeangliae: assessing polygyny and skew in male reproductive success”. Animal Behaviour, 70(2): p.267-277.
Crecimiento de los hombres sin sexo con la revolución sexual:
https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2019/03/29/share-americans-not-having-sex-has-reached-record-high/?noredirect=on
Alguien que tenga una calidad inferior como pareja potencial tendrá que trabajar más duro en la fase posterior al match para lograr éxito. La calidad varía en función del sexo. Las mujeres tienen generalmente mayor valor que los hombres en el mercado sexual las personas menos atractivas tienen que hacer más este tipo de trabajo que las más atractivas, que los hombres tengan que hacer más que las mujeres, las mujeres mayores que hagan más que las mujeres más jóvenes y los hombres con menos recursos para hacer más de lo que hombres con más recursos.
Olivera-La Rosa, A., Arango-Tobón, O. E., & Ingram, G. P. (2019). Swiping right: face perception in the age of Tinder. Heliyon, 5(12).
El modelo de relaciones a corto plazo es solo beneficioso solo para unos pocos, para los demás lo es invertir esfuerzo y recursos en la mujer y la descendencia.
Gangestad, S. W., & Simpson, J. A. (2000). “The evolution of human mating: Trade-offs and strategic pluralism”. Behavioral and brain sciences, 23(4): p. 573-587. 
La mayoría de hombres juega a la estadística dando match a todas las mujeres indiscriminadamente. Sin embargo un mayor número de intentos no garantiza un mayor número de éxitos. Las mujeres generalmente tienen un mayor número de matches en Tinder que los hombres. Los hombres son los que inician la mayoría de conversaciones. Las redes sociales de ligue no sirven únicamente para el sexo casual como generalmente se suele decir, también para relaciones comprometidas.
Timmermans, E., & Courtois, C. (2018). “From swiping to casual sex and/or committed relationships: Exploring the experiences of Tinder users”. The Information Society, 34(2): p.59-70.
No existe diferencia entre las redes sociales y la vida real:
Hodkinson, K. & Gatter, K. (2016). “On the differences between Tinder™ versus online dating agencies: Questioning a myth. An exploratory study”. Cogent Psychology, 3(1).

description.original:
Whales are the largest animals on the planet, and until now, there hasn’t been a method to estimate their body mass in the wild. A study released today (October 2) in Methods in Ecology and Evolution describes a way to estimate the mass of whales from images captured by drones. 

Led by Fredrik Christiansen from the Aarhus Institute of Advanced Studies in Denmark, researchers used photographs from drones to take body measurements of 86 southern right whales (Eubalaena australis) near Península Valdés, Argentina. The team then developed a model to predict body volume from these measurements. They used data from historical catch records to predict volume and calculate whale density, and from there, estimated body mass of the whales they observed. 

Read more at the-scientist.com.

Credit: FREDERIK CHRISTIANSEN (2019)
Video was taken under research permit.

MANDATORY ONSCREEN CREDIT - Jodi Frediani

These friendly whales gave stunned tourists a welcome to remember as they swam right up to their boats to say hello.
 
Whale watchers in the Dominican Republic were blown away as a mum and baby popped up to say hi and breached the water several times.
 
Moments later, the lucky spectators were thrilled once again when two more friendly humpbacks took a liking to the boat's vibrating engine and swam right up to their vessel.
 
The huge whales appeared to enjoy the attention they received - staying putting for several minutes and wowing the crowd.

description.original:
Humpback whales are one of the most beautiful and awe-inspiring animals on the planet. They are majestic and enormous, creating an appreciation for how small and fragile humans are in comparison. Being lucky enough to see one in the wild is an unforgettable experience. It is only then that we can fully grasp how massive and powerful they are. But actually swimming beside one is a thrill that cannot even be described. Weighing as much as 30 tons (27,000kg) and reaching 52 feet in length (24m), they are among the true giants of the ocean. These lucky swimmers had traveled to The Kingdom of Tonga, in the South Pacific Islands, to see the animals close up. Part of a tour with a certified guide, they carefully slipped into the water to observe this mother and her baby from a distance. They couldn't believe their good fortune when the mother turned and lazily drifted towards them for a closer look. Humpbacks are curious and very tolerant of humans but they are usually more reserved when they have a newborn. This mother seemed unconcerned as she and her baby closed the gap and looked at everyone closely. The swimmers moved back a few times, as required, keeping a respectful and safe distance. Their fins appear in the video as they swim backwards to move away. It is for the benefit of the animals that closer contact is avoided, and also for the safety of the people since humpbacks are powerful and heavy. It appears that this mother might have been providing her baby with a lesson in how to inspect the strange creatures that can be found in the water and she repeatedly drifted right to them. For almost ten minutes, floated and turned, moving very slowly in the direction of the swimmers. Mother humpbacks come to Tonga to give birth because it is one of the few places in the ocean where killer whales do not go. Humpbacks fear only large sharks and killer whales, and their babies are vulnerable to both of these predators in the first few months of life. The mother keeps her calf close to her head and she will lift it out of the water to protect it if a threat appears. The baby instinctively knows that this is where it should be but it swam around and rolled a few times as if tempted to play with the humans. Humpback whales are also one of the most intelligent creatures on earth, having an intellect comparable to dolphins and chimpanzees. Until as recently as 100,000 years ago, it is believed they were the smartest of all creatures on our planet. Looking onto the eyes of one of these beautiful whales, it's not hard to appreciate the wisdom and intellectual capacity behind their gaze. Anyone who has ever been in the presence of a humpback is simply not the same afterwards. Losing these whales to pollution, harvesting, or anything else would be tragic beyond words. Our oceans would not be the same without them.

Source & embed code: https://rumble.com/v8q8kj-mother-humpback-brings-her-newborn-baby-to-inspect-delighted-swimmers.html.

For licensing, please email licensing@rumble.com.

THIS SHOULD BE WATCHED ON THE BIGGEST SCREEN WITH THE BEST SOUND YOU CAN GET. WATCH TO THE END WITH SOME OF THE BEST KEPT TO LAST. VOTE FOR YOUR FAVOURITE IN OUR POLL (OR COMMENT BELOW)

A couple of years ago, Multihull Central in partnership with Cruising Helmsman Magazine (also sponsored by Wasp cam, AMS, Pantaenius Insurance), held a competition for the best short films about cruising adventures to help inspire others. We were inundated with entries and NOT from the usual YouTube sources, but from amazing armature film makers and story tellers out at sea. The following films were what the judges considered the most inspiring and represented the meaning of a seabbatical. This full collection of the best short films was first shown in a cinema that was especially hired with a packed audience at the Sanctuary Cove Boat Show and has not be seen since. 

During these times of isolation, we thought it would be great to revisit these amazing moments of inspiration to remind us of the great adventures that can be had around the world and keep planning for the future. 

So sit back, get some popcorn, put it on the big screen, turn up the volume and enjoy the show. And don't forget to vote for your favourite film in our POLL at the very end, or comment below.

A physician who can talk to animals embarks on an adventure to find a legendary island with a young apprentice and a crew of strange pets.

Cast:
▶ Robert Downey Jr. as Dr. John Dolittle, a widowed veterinarian who has the ability to speak to animals.
▶ Harry Collett as Tommy Stubbins, Dolittle's self-appointed apprentice.
▶ Antonio Banderas as King Rassouli, the king of pirates who was Lily's father and Dolittle’s father-in-law.
▶ Emma Thompson as Polynesia, a wise and brave macaw and Dolittle’s most trusted advisor.
▶ Rami Malek as Chee-Chee, a shy but noble gorilla.
▶ John Cena as Yoshi, a happy-go-lucky but always cold polar bear who wears a chullo.
▶ Kumail Nanjiani as Plimpton, a mischievous and critical but well-meaning ostrich who wears striped stockings and quarrels with Yoshi.
▶ Octavia Spencer as Dab-Dab, a helpful but deluded duck with a metal leg.
▶ Tom Holland as Jip, a loyal dog who wears glasses.
▶ Craig Robinson as Kevin, a cheeky-chappy squirrel with attitude.
▶ Ralph Fiennes as Barry, an aggressive Bengal tiger who has a past with Dolittle and wants to please his mum.
▶ Selena Gomez as Betsy, a friendly giraffe.
▶ Marion Cotillard as Tutu, a French fox who is best friends with Betsy.
▶ Jason Mantzoukas as James, a comical dragonfly who meets Dolittle in a prison cell from which he helps him escape.
▶ Frances de la Tour as Ginko-Who-Soars, a fire-breathing dragon who guards a magical fruit.
▶ Michael Sheen as Dr. Blair Müdfly, an old schoolmate and rival of Dolittle who gradually becomes impressed by Dolittle's special ability.
▶ Jim Broadbent as Lord Thomas Badgley, one of the Queen's dishonest chairmen.
▶ Jessie Buckley as Queen Victoria, the Queen of England.
▶ Carmel Laniado as Lady Rose, a maid of honor to the Queen and Tommy's friend.
▶ Kasia Smutniak as Lily Dolittle, Dolittle's wife and King Rassouli's daughter.

description.original:
This small ship cruise, aboard a classic converted tugboat with just 12 guests, explores the best of Alaska’s inside passage. On your expedition get close and personal with icebergs, glaciers, humpback whales, marine mammals, sea birds, sea otters. Walk the rainforests, view brown bears, soak in natural hot springs. Visit the historic towns, anchor, in remote coves.

This odyssey is a sweeping exploration of southeast Alaska. Fredrick Sound, Endicott Arm, Warm Springs Bay, and Pack Creek to see humpback whales, a tidal glacier, and brown bears. Travel south into the Etolin Wilderness Area, Myers Chuck, and Ketchikan.

Here at Maple Leaf Adventures, we are a small ship eco-tourism company that prides ourselves on our expert crew, beautiful vessels, and slow travel that really allows our guests to experience the best of Alaska.

description.original:
Cabo Trek your BEST option for "Whale Watching in Cabo San Lucas" !

Starting from SEASON 2019/2020 Cabo Trek wants to be innovative and offer whale watching from a new location: SAN JOSE' DEL CABO

This decision has been made because after our research it is our believe that we can offer a great experience to our guest.
We believe that we will be able to find more lonely whales, meaning that there will be fewer boats around!

By offering 3 hour tours on board of a comfortable 35ft yacht we will be able to explore the Sea of Cortez more in depth and enjoy the spectacular acrobatic behaviors of the Humpback Whales.

The vessel is equipped with big roof cover for plenty of shade and of course it has a spacious restroom. 

Surely a good option for guests who already stay in San Jose' del Cabo or for families or generally for people who prefer bigger boats.

As usual the tour will be guided by a Marine Biologist who will amaze you with a great deal of information and curiosities. After already 3 full years of research studying the whale tails there is so much we already know about the Humpbacks who visit Baja California every year!

Join us in this NEW whale watching in San Jose' del Cabo adventure!

http://www.cabowhaletrek.com
-----
-----

Whale Watching season in Cabo San Lucas starts the 15th of December and ends the 15th of April of each year! 
Scuba diving and Snorkeling? all year round!

Cabo Trek focus is to provide excellent customer service, our boats are new and comfortable, shade is provided as well as a marine toilet. Seats are cushioned and there is plenty of room for everybody since we keep our groups small (max. 10 people).

description.original:
This incredible footage, originally uploaded in early 2018, appears to show a 50,000-pound humpback whale pushing a snorkeler through the water, to protect her from a nearby shark. 

The stunning collection of videos Nan Hauser and her team were able to capture show how the whale pushed biologist Nan with his head and his mouth, tucked her under its pectoral fin - even lifted the biologist out of the water on one occasion.

The moment, Nan, 63, said, is perhaps proof of whale's intuitive nature to protect other species of animal -  including humans - something she believes has never been captured on film, and intuition the biologist compared to firemen being willing to rush into a house on fire to help save the lives of those they do not know.

--

description.original:
Five years ago today, the rogue poaching vessel Thunder was scuttled by its own crew after a 110-day high-seas chase by Sea Shepherd as part of Operation Icefish. 

At the start of Operation Icefish in 2014, Sea Shepherd set out to locate and shut down illegal, unreported and unregulated fishing in Antarctica. Infamously named the "Bandit 6", the targets were six illegal poaching vessels known to Interpol and CCAMLR, who had previously managed to evade any law enforcement. Over two campaigns that spanned from 2014 to 2016, Sea Shepherd set the world record for the longest high-seas pursuit of a poaching vessel, removed 72 kilometers of illegal gillnets from the ocean, and successfully shut down all of the Bandit 6 vessels.

----

Sea Shepherd is an international, non-profit marine conservation organization that engages in direct action campaigns to defend wildlife and conserve and protect the world’s oceans from illegal exploitation and environmental destruction.

Learn more about us: https://www.seashepherdglobal.org/
Support our efforts: https://www.seashepherdglobal.org/donate/

description.original:
Orcas, or killer whales, are the largest of the dolphins and one of the world's most powerful predators. They're immediately recognizable by their distinctive black-and-white coloring. Orcas are a toothed whales belonging to the oceanic dolphin family. Killer whales have a diverse diet, although individual populations often specialize in particular types of prey. Some feed exclusively on fish, while others hunt marine mammals such as seals and other species of dolphin.

description.original:
Dozens of fishermen and volunteers in Zorritos, Tumbes, Peru, came together to save a beached humpback whale on Wednesday who had been washed up on shore after being entangled in fishing nets on Tuesday .
Using rope and pushing with their bare hands, volunteers managed to get the whale - measuring from eight to 10 metres (26.2 feet to 32.8 feet) long - back into the sea.
The volunteers cheered as the whale began swimming of its own accord after making it past the breaking surf.
Humpback whales, once prized by hunters for their blubber, can weigh up to 40 tons and span 60 feet in length. Humpbacks are best known for periodically jumping out of the water, or breaching, behaviour that has attracted throngs of people who take to the seas to engage in whale-watching.....

Take in the glow of Diamond head at golden hour and the magic of the Honolulu city lights from an all-new luxury powerboat! Ocean and You is the premier Oahu experience for an intimate Waikiki sunset cruise.

With transportation from Waikiki hotels included, board the double-decker boat and explore its wraparound seating and Titanic-style front railing. Enjoy pupus (appetizers) and island cuisine prepared by local Hawaiian chef Elmer Guzman. Keep your eyes on the horizon for sightings of Hawaiian spinner dolphins, or humpback whales in winter.

Then, sit back and relax while the local crew entertains you with hula dancing and shares information on Hawaiian culture.

To take the same tour for yourself or explore other parts of Hawaii, visit our website www.andyoucreations.com.

His passion for seeing whales started at a young age, when he saw a blue whale while working as a deck boy. After that he always wanted to see a blue whale again, and he sure did! description.original:
Mazunte es una de las playas más bonitas y poco conocidas de Oaxaca. El primer día que despiertes aquí te recibirá un cielo azul, un clima caluroso y el sonido del suave oleaje.

Por la tarde un cielo anaranjando te invitará a la contemplación y relajarte, lo cual es cada vez menos frecuente en otras playas mexicanas. La gente es amable, cualquiera te puede dar pistas de cómo pasartela bien.

Para que te enamores más de Mazunte te presentamos algunos de sus mejores lugares para visitar.

1. Punta cometa

En el extremo occidental de la bahía Mazunte se forma una media luna conocida como Punta Cometa, no solo te recomendamos que vayas a este lugar por tener acceso a algunos de los mejores amaneceres de la costa sino también porque al lugar se le considera un  lugar cósmico y energético. 

2.  Centro Mexicano de la Tortuga

Aunque no lo creas Mazunte no siempre fue el paraíso que hoy conocemos, antes era el rastro tortuguero más grande de México, hasta 1990 cuando el gobierno prohibió esta práctica. El Centro Mexicano de la Tortuga, ubicado en Mazunte, te permite colaborar con ellos en el rescate de estos reptiles con voluntariados de mínimo un mes. 

3. Come en la Estrella Fugaz

Es considerado uno de los mejores lugares para comer en Mazunte, es admirado por sus cafés, desayunos riquísimos. Tienen un pequeño local llamado Kapricho, especilizado en ofrecer ceviches, ensalsadas y sandwiches.

4. Practíca Skimboard

Para los que practican los deportes acuáticos Mazunte es especial por la forma en que aquí rompen las olas. Atrévete a subirte a una tabla de skimboarding, una tabla más corta y ancha que las de surf. Para realizar esta actividad pregunta en dónde está el Mazunteskim, ellos te orientarán.

5. Avistamiento de ballenas jorobadas

Si tienes planeado visitar este paraíso oaxaqueño en un futuro cercano te recomendamos que lo hagas entre diciembre y marzo. Durante está temporada las ballenas jorobadas migran por las playas de Mazunte. Por lo que puedes admirar de este espectacular animal desde Cerro Sagrado.

Pisar la dorada arena de Mazunte, mientras el mantra de sus olas te arrulla con su vaivén de suave tonalidad turquesa será como caer un paraíso.

En Mazunte tus días transcurrirán lentamente. Te contagiarás de la pasividad del oleaje que pareciera no tener prisa para alcanzar la orilla de la playa, o del sol que calmo atraviesa el cielo hasta el atardecer; cuando la oscuridad llega muy lentamente parece que se despierta la poesía visual a su paso pues mientras la noche cae el radiante naranja del sol se oculta y comienzan a salir los grillos para acompañarlo con su canto; es una dulzura que casi podrás tocar. Los únicos testigos serán tú y las tortugas que regresan a casa.

Nuestra presencia Digital:

www.LugaresTuristicosEnMexico.com

Redes Sociales:
https://www.facebook.com/LugaresTuristicosMexico

description.original:
Inspired by photos on Instagram of a stunning rock formation and a book called Secret Cornwall, we set out to find Nanjizal Bay. 

Joins us as we walk through farmland and tracks to reach this special cove, litter with pebble the size of dinosaur eggs and a scramble over some hefty rocks, we eventually reach the marvel, the Song of the Sea.

This walk, is a there and back walk. We park in Trevescan, a little hamlet near Lands End, walk via footpaths down to Nanjizal Bay. This walk in total is just over 2 miles.

For an annotated video and written walk instructions, please join us on Patreon: https://www.patreon.com/Cornishwalkingtrails

Credit to: The book we used to help us find Nanjizal Bay is called Secret Cornwall, by Sue Bradbury. Published by Tor Mark Press.

Act now! https://act.seashepherdglobal.org/turtles/

Every year, tons of discarded fishing gear wash up on the beaches of Cabo Verde a remote island nation in the central Atlantic Ocean, where thousands of loggerhead sea turtles come to lay their eggs. Sea Shepherd and local conservation organization Biosfera have teamed up to remove this deadly fishing gear from the beaches and stop it from choking the mother and baby turtles before they safely reach the waters. 

But we need your help! Click here to take action now: https://act.seashepherdglobal.org/turtles/

----

Sea Shepherd is an international, non-profit marine conservation organization that engages in direct action campaigns to defend wildlife, and conserve and protect the world’s oceans from illegal exploitation and environmental destruction.

description.original:
#whales #danapoint #captdaves

Three migrating gray whales seem to enjoy each other's company, and that of their common dolphin companions, in this drone video filmed off the coast of Dana Point, California, in March 2019.

Gray whales make one of the longest migrations of any mammal. Traveling every year along the U.S. West Coast from their feeding grounds north of Alaska to their mating and birthing lagoons in Baja California, Mexico. Once called "devil fish" by whale hunters, gray whales are now known as the "friendly whale", thanks to their amiable behavior towards boats and the inclination to bring their calves over to be touched by humans in the protected lagoons.

➡️ Learn more about gray whales: https://www.dolphinsafari.com/gray-whales/

*****
🐳 Captain Dave's Dolphin and Whale Watching Safari offers five-star, eco-friendly, dolphin & whale watching experiences with award-winning customer service.

Located in Dana Point, California, the Dolphin and Whale Watching Capital of the World®. Multiple unique and uncrowded vessels include a Catamaran Sailboat with 2 Eye-to-Eye Underwater Viewing Pods and an intimate, high-speed Zodiac.

description.original:
In this video, Gulf Coast Nation heads offshore in search of some Amberjack, given the recent season opening! But in the northern Gulf of Mexico, this time of year, you never know what you might find!! 

We ran into school of thousands and thousands of False Albacore (Little Tunie) and we got tons of shark bait for the upcoming winter season!! We eventually got our 4 man limit and had to leave the fish biting because we couldn't catch another fish. We were on these schools from 930am-230pm. It was an epic and exhausting  day!

We have 2 GIANT deep freezers where we stored all the fish and every single fish will be used very soon!!

Reels- Tsunami Saltx 6000, Tsunami Evict 4000, Daiwa BG 3500

Hi Friends,

In this video we rent a jetski and make our way to Iguana Island and the famous La Famille Express. 

Providenciales is the best place to rent Jetskis, you need to do your homework as everyone charges a different price. All of the tour operators are also charging different prices for the same tour. We recommend skilling the tour and renting your own Jetski or boat and doing the tour yourself. 

We rented our Jetskis from Tropical Waves Water Sports at sapodilla bay beach and we found them to be professional and offer the best pricing. It's also a great place to relax as they have a bar, restaurant and other amenities for you to use while you are at the beach.

••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••

"Die Seiten vom Floß wollen wir ein wenig schnittig halten. Erste Tests wie wir den Ausbau dort vornehmen laufen ...

... damit uns der gute Haifisch nicht alles wegfuttert, müssen wir die Fundamente vor Ort direkt verstärken. Gut, dass wir an einer kleinen Insel anlegen können. Wir füllen unseren Vorrat an Schrott direkt wieder auf."

Gefangen auf einem kleinen Floß mit nichts als einem Haken aus altem Plastik, erwachen die Spieler auf dem Blauer Ozean ganz allein und ohne Land in Sicht! Mit trockenem Hals und leerem Magen wird Überleben nicht einfach!

The Grand Princess is set to arrive to San Francisco Thursday, March 5 with several suspected cases of coronavirus. 
File Video, filmed June 27, 2017.

I spotted the Grand Princess cruise ship arriving under the Golden Gate Bridge on June 27, 2017. I don't know where the cruise ship was coming from, and it was about 9:30 a.m. at the time of filming. 

I'm sharing this video publicly on YouTube following its use on-air on KTVU FOX 2 throughout the afternoon and evening on March 4, 2020.

ペルセウス座流星群はほぼ終わりましたが、ここ木曽の夜空ならいつも１０分で一つくらいは流れ星が見られます。

description.original:
A group of locals jumped into the surf in Lambayeque, Peru, Tuesday, August 13, to make a valiant effort to save a beached whale.
The locals pushed on the whale's sides and its massive tail as they attempted to assist it back to deeper water.
Local media reported the whale measured about 10 meters and weighed approximately 6.5 tons.
While local media did not report the species of whale Tuesday, two humpback whales have washed up on Peruvian beaches in the past 15 days. (Reuters)
title.original: Local Heroes Try to Rescue Beached Whale in Peru

description.original:
Humpback whales are amongst the biggest known mammals on Earth, weighing in at around 36.000kg, but by the early 1960s, after 34 million years on this planet, these gentle, majestic giants had been hunted almost to extinction. With their populations now in partial recovery, it is once again possible to find humpback whales around Rurutu in Polynesian waters. They congregate here between July and November to give birth to a new generation, and to mate. The newborns are prepared for a life of migration, covering thousands of kilometres every single year.

description.original:
ボクハワEP9は朝食を食べた後からスタート！
トイレを探しにマサ＆ジョイスオカズヤ近くのショッピングセンター「ウインドワードシティショッピングセンター」へ行きました。
そこにあったロングスドラッグスが朝7時から営業していたので、ロングスでトイレを探しました。そしたら意外な所を案内され・・。
その後行ったホオマルヒアボタアニカルガーデンは、美しい緑と花の宝庫でした。どうぞご覧ください！

2019.10.23～30　11回目のハワイ旅行へ6泊8日で行ってまいりました。
今年もレンタカーでオアフ島ローカルエリアを走り回り　★美味しいもの　★綺麗な景色　をたくさん食べて・見てきました。
今回のシリーズも長ーく続きますので、是非チャンネル登録をお願いします！！

●インスタグラムはこちら！
　https://www.instagram.com/alphasensecomplete/

　軽キャン・ハワイ・音楽・プライベート　などの写真をアップしてます。

【ボクハワ的ハワイ旅行のスタイル】

　ローカルエリアをレンタカーで巡る旅。早朝からワイキキエリアを飛び出して、オアフ島のいろんなローカルエリアへ行き、ガイドブックには載っていない場所やグルメを自己流で探す。そして夜には寝るためにワイキキのホテルに戻る。そんな旅のスタイルです。日本人観光客の少ないエリアを旅するため、ブランドショップなどは全くと言っていいほど出てきません（笑）そして私たちは英語がほぼ喋れません。それなのに日本語がほぼ通じないエリアへと行くので、いつも「言葉の壁」にぶち当たります。でもハワイの人は優しい方が多いので「ハワイ好きの日本人観光客」の私たちにいつも親切にしてくれます。僕はそんなハワイが大好きです。

　何回かハワイへ行ったことがあるけど「もう少し自由にハワイを旅してみたい」・・そんなふうに考えている方へ、この動画が少しでも参考になったり、また初めてハワイへ行く方へは、動画の中に出てくるたくさんの美しいスポットを見て、ハワイ旅行へ行くきっかけになったら嬉しいです。そんな私もまだまだハワイの知らない場所がたくさんありますけど（笑）。
僕はたぶん一生ハワイに通い続けるでしょう！
みなさまののコメントお待ちしております！

description.original:
South Carolina goofyfoot vagabond Cam Richards is no stranger to wild, bucking bronco waves at Pipeline, as evidenced by last year's O'Neill Wave of the Winter contender. And on opening day at Pipe this past Monday, he managed an eerily similar ride.

“It was a pretty bumpy morning,” he said. “Not too good, but you could tell there was a few — and not too crowded. So it was a good time to get out there, especially with it being the first Pipe swell. I had a bunch of bad ones before, and swung at that one last-minute — it didn’t look too good, and then I almost ate it on the drop. And then I recovered and did one big pump and it spit and I was blind for the whole wave, just waiting to get lipped in the head. And then it cleared up, and I was lucky enough to doggy door. It was super fun and looking forward to the rest of the season. Couldn’t ask for a better start.”

Surfer: Cam Richards
Video: Nate Neal

description.original:
A few species of animals can look a lot like dolphins, especially from a distance. Video clips and information about distinguishing features of harbor porpoise, common dolphins, bottlenose dolphins,  Dall's porpoise, Pacific white-sided dolphins, and killer whales are featured in this video. Many of these species, except for harbor porpoise and killer whales, are not commonly seen in Puget Sound and researchers would like to learn more about the presence and behavior of these animals.  Please contact Cascadia Research to report sightings of unusual marine mammal species. http://www.cascadiaresearch.org/

Harbor porpoise (0:10)
Common dolphins (0:52)
Bottlenose dolphins (1:53)
Dall's porpoise (2:49)
Pacific white-sided dolphins (4:06)
Killer whales (4:47)
title.original: Was that a dolphin I saw in Puget Sound?

description.original: Gray whales are traveling north on their way to the summer feeding grounds in Alaska. Watch our live stream as we watch for the tell-tale blow, the spray of ocean water that says a whale is here! If we're lucky, we may see a whale breach as it launches as much as 3/4 of its body out of the water in a spectacular show of power and grace. The live-stream is brought to you by Oregon State Parks and the Oregon Whale Watch Program. Want to learn more? Go to http://www.orwhalewatch.org for more news about gray whales. Visit http://www.oregonstateparks.org for state park, campground and reservation information, as well as Oregon State Park merchandise in the Park Store.

description.original:
We start to make preparations for leaving the Kingdom of Tonga to sail to Norfolk Island via the beautiful Minerva Reef. We’ve heard that the crayfish are fabulous on the south reef so we’re going to check it out.

We pick up a few last minute food supplies and do the final boat jobs that need to be done for the next passage.

Magnus finally manages to fix the problem which is causing Izzy, the engine, to continually fill up with salt water! The autopilot clutch is fixed, yet again. We’re hoping it will make it all the way to Australia. The sails get a few stitches, hatches get resealed and Nutshell gets a big tidy up.

We know that Australia is very strict with quarantine when entering, so give Nutshell a good clean and clear out unwanted and not needed items, in preparation for Australian customs.

Wendy makes a new courtesy flag for our Norfolk Island arrival.

Oh, and we show you how convoluted the process is for finding customs to check out of Tonga!

Thanks for watching and following along with our adventures.

Wendy and Magnus


______

description.original:
朝日新聞社と東京大学の天文台がコラボし、星空ライブを始めました。

ペルセウス座流星群はほぼ終わりましたが、ここ木曽の夜空ならいつも１０分で一つくらいは流れ星が見られます。

ライブカメラが写しているのは北東の空。この時期はカシオペア座やペルセウス座が見えます。天候にかかわらず配信しますので、曇っちゃったらごめんなさい。

協力：東京大学大学院理学系研究科附属天文学教育研究センター木曽観測所（長野県木曽郡）。ドームにあるのはシュミット式で世界最大級の「105cmシュミット望遠鏡」。最新の動画カメラ「トモエゴゼン（Tomo-e Gozen）」を装備して試験観測中です。

ライブカメラの画角は左右70度、上下50度。16mmF1.4、ISO100-204800

description.original: Ninja stealth mode. Due to it being pup season, I need to be really cautious about disturbance in the colonies. I spent the last few days developing some tools for a new technique. As the seals don’t have great eyesight, I found a large female with some netting gagging her and looped around the back of her head. It tools about 10 minutes of slow crawling to infiltrate the group and I got about 2 meters away without causing disturbance. The video doesn’t give justice to the size of the Bull that came to check me out and made me feel real small and vulnerable.... Obviously I didn’t have the luxury of removing the whole entanglement, but with it being cut the tension is off, which is instant pain relief, and it will surely fall off soon as she splashes around in the water again.

description.original:
Newfoundland and Labrador form the most easterly province of Canada. On Newfoundland island, the Norse archaeological site L'Anse aux Meadows is the reputed settlement of Viking explorer Leif Erikson. Gros Morne National Park, on the Gulf of St Lawrence, has cliffs, waterfalls and glacial fjords. Southeastern capital city St. John’s is known for the 17th-century Signal Hill citadel, with a hillside walking trail.
Population: 521,542 (2019) 
Capital: St. John's
Newfoundland and Labrador, the journey can be as colourful as stories told around the kitchen table. As meandering as our thousands of kilometres of coastline. As surprising as a humpback whale breaching in the mist. Or as comforting as bakeapple jam. There are places that travel with you, wherever you go.
Visit : https://www.newfoundlandlabrador.com/

#Canada #NewfoundandandLabrado #Beautyplace

description.original:
Off Marseille (French coast), a couple of Fin whales have been spotted reclaiming waters that are not so busy with international shipping dramatically reduced. I have been wondering how much the air and other areas will reduce in pollution as we have already seen animals entering towns and cities that are devoid of humans the three days of air grounding after 9/11 (in 2001) cleared up the air dramatically, could something happen again here with reduced air travel? Scientists will have a perfect opportunity to observe all this and more at this time. We shall have to wait and see. They will avoid it once the world economy gears up again, no doubt.

1) John Hopkins world map (real time stats and clickable map features): 
https://coronavirus.jhu.edu/map.html

2) There is now a Coronavirus (Covid-19) playlist on this channel:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=frGyZ30Aq6o&list=PL93gCV9Iym3dh_FjdQ_2pum9Vk--oTdyF

description.original:
Releasing stress through the facility of Meditation Relaxing Music:
Music can have a profound effect on both the emotions and therefore the body. Faster music can cause you to feel more alert and concentrate better. Upbeat Relaxing Music can cause you to feel more optimistic and positive about life. A slower tempo can quiet your mind and relax your muscles, making you're feeling soothed while releasing the strain of the day. Meditation Music is effective for relaxation and stress management.

OneVideo need to Research confirms these personal experiences with music. Search as relaxing music, meditation music, sleep music, calming music, spa music, relaxing sleep music, baby sleep music, relaxing piano music, soothing music, soft music, the honest guys relaxing music with water sounds meditation, sleep hypnosis, deep sleep music, sleep music soothing relaxation, zen music, music for sleeping relaxing sleep music, sleep music deep sleeping music, massage music, peaceful music, relaxing music for stress relief, piano music.

Current findings indicate that music around 60 beats per minute can cause the brain to synchronize with the beat causing alpha brainwaves (frequencies from 8 - 14 hertz or cycles per second). 

This alpha brainwave is what's present once we are relaxed and conscious. To induce sleep (a delta brainwave of 5 hertz), an individual may have to devote a minimum of 45 minutes, during a relaxed position, taking note of calming music.

 Researchers at Stanford University have said that "listening to music seems to be ready to change brain functioning to an equivalent extent as medication." They noted that music is some things that nearly anybody can access and makes it a simple stress reduction tool.

So what sort of music reduces stress the best? A touch surprising is that Native American, Celtic, Indian stringed-instruments, drums, and flutes are very effective at relaxing the mind even when played moderately loud. 

Sounds of rain, thunder, and nature sounds also can be relaxing particularly when mixed with other music, like light jazz, classical (the "largo" movement), and easy listening music. 

Since with music we are rarely told the beats per minute, how does one choose the relief music that's best for you? The solution partly rests with you: you want to first just like the music being played, and then it must relax you. 

You’ll start by simply exploring the music on this website. Some may relax you, some might not. Forcing yourself to concentrate to relaxation music that irritates you'll create tension, not reduce it.

 If that happens, try trying to find alternatives on the web or consult counseling maintenance staff for other musical suggestions.

 It’s important to recollect that quieting your mind doesn't mean you'll automatically feel sleepy. It means your brain and body are relaxed, and together with your new calm self, you'll then function at your best in many activities.

Relaxing Music – e.g. for studying, yoga, or to calm your mind: Use this soft and peaceful, relaxing and possibly inspiring music video e.g. as background music at work, while studying, reception while relaxing, for your yoga sessions, while reading, while gaming, reflecting, thinking, planning, or maybe while meditating.

Meditation music:
When you want the right music to go with your yoga or meditation practice, look no further.

This page starts with a playlist that has a tremendous selection of soothing, relaxing and calming music. Because of Eddy Tony from BPM Fitness for originally producing these videos on his YouTube channel. Following the playlist we've a set of fantastic one off videos.

Sleep is an important phase of our life. We’d like it to realize a restorative rest that prepares of for the new day. The hours of sleep permit us to flush trivial worries and integrate our outer experiences so we will awaken refreshed and prepared for the challenges of the new day. 

Sleep is super important:
Because sleep is so important, we'd like to organize for it to make sure that our sleep are going to be restful and effective. While the method is automatic for several, others need help to quiet their worried mind, calming anxieties, and adjusting expectations.

 In order that we rest our mind from our challenges and concerns also as our tired body.

HUNTINGTON BEACH - The Huntington Beach Pier an Icon for Orange County and Surf City USA will be closed.  The closure comes after the public guidelines for proper social distancing were not met.  The closure is for the amphitheater area and pier and will be closed until further notice.  The city of HB has put out signs and tape for the areas under the closure including parking lots and volleyball areas.  Due to the closure the iconic Ruby's Diner will also be closed.

description.original:
This camera watches over Gowrie dam on Djuma Game Reserve, in the Sabi Sand Wildtuin, South Africa. In fact this is the oldest waterhole cam in Africa and the world. It’s been broadcasting LIVE from this spot since 1998. With some luck you will see big cats coming for a drink o even on a kill close by. You can also expect to see a lot of impala (light brown antelope), waterbuck (white circle on rump), nyala (males have yellow legs and females have white stripes on flanks) and many other types of mammals, birds and reptiles.

The camera is remotely controlled by a volunteer corps of people around the world known as ‘zoomies’. They log into the camera according to a schedule in shifts, and pan, tilt and zoom in search of animals. They also Tweet sightings @WildEarth Djuma was started almost twenty years ago as a safari, lodge by the Moolman family, and is renowned for the quality of its game safaris.
title.original: Djuma Private Game Reserve Live Stream

description.original:
Killer whales are the best predators that dominate the world's oceans.
Not only in strength, but in intelligence, it overwhelms almost all animals.
The male adult is 9.8meters and weighs 10 tons.
Do you remember the movie, Free Willy, with this killer whale as its main character?
Killer whales are unlikely to be tamed by humans.
Shamu is performing at SeaWorld in San Antonio, USA
This is Sea World's mascot.
Shall we watch Shamu's show "Once one" at SeaWorld?

Shamu is the nickname for killer whales at Sea World.
SeaWorld has been criticized by animal lovers.
Because they are taming killer whales for the show.
The killer whale called Geiko, the protagonist of the movie Free Willy
went back to the sea again.
Geiko, who has become accustomed to the care of people,
Unfortunately, died from hunger and pneumonia.
If it hadn't been tamed by human hands from the beginning
it would have been free to swim in the sea and live happily with the crowd.
Nowadays, we realize that humans and nature must coexist.

Video credit: videvo

Music provided by 브금대통령
Track : The First Noel (Covered by 루이드) - https://youtu.be/6zi-fYr_FJg

description.original:
Started streaming on June 26, 2017

Welcome to Virtual Railfan, please read the important info below.

You are watching a live stream of Tower 55 in Fort Worth, Texas, for people who enjoy watching trains. You are welcome to join our family friendly chat, but keep in mind that there’s a community with rules already established.  Please check them out. 

Duplication or distribution of our videos is strictly prohibited without permission.

CHAT RULES:

• Be polite and respectful
• Use English, we need a single language to be able to understand each other. If you’re not fluent, please use a translator such as Google Translate.
• Don’t post in ALL CAPS or use excessive emojis.
• Don’t discuss politics, religion, race, sex, violence, train or vehicle accidents, or anything like that. We try to be mindful of any children who may be watching. 
• The conversation here is trains, and please remember that said on topic conversation needs to come first. Off topic conversation such as music, sports, jokes, etc. is fine, but it must be kept in balance with on topic.
• Please keep conversations of personal issues (medical, domestic, legal, etc.) out of the chat; take it to messaging or email. Remember, you are sharing information with hundreds of people, not just those directly involved in the chat.
• Don’t ask to become a moderator. It’s earned. If we’re interested in your assistance, we will contact you.
• Just be nice, it’s amazing what happens when we’re all nice to each other.

THINGS THAT WILL GET YOU BANNED: 

• Inappropriate usernames
• Profanity
• Asking for subscriptions (subs)
• Being intentionally disruptive, creating arguments or any other jerk-like behavior 
• Not following the moderators’ instructions 

ABOUT THIS FEED:

Tower 55 is located in Fort Worth, Texas. The camera is the SW quadrant of the crossing, mounted on the NE corner of the Morrison Supply Company. There are more than 100 freight trains that travel through here a day - UP, BNSF and FWWR. Amtrak runs two trains daily that pass through here, #21 & 22, the Texas Eagle. You can see the Trinity Railway Express (TRE) line in the background as well.

When’s the next train? Yeah, we get this a lot. You can figure out the next Amtrak passenger train with this handy link: https://bit.ly/2M4bFLF

There’s no schedule for freight trains, but some of our more knowledgeable members will provide real-time information when it’s available. Please refrain from asking.

ABOUT VIRTUAL RAILFAN:

Virtual Railfan currently has nearly 50 cams from 3 countries. Visit our website for memberships, more free cams, and our own live chat. Thanks for stopping by, we’re glad you’re here!

In less than 10 hours, the highly anticipated Bitcoin halving will be activated. But, whales seem to be taking the opportunity to dump on the market. Since Friday, bitcoin price dropped by more than 14% from $10,020 to $8,550. At its lowest point on May 10, it reached $8,100, marking a 20% decline ahead of the halving. The Bitcoin blockchain network is primarily divided into three groups: developers, users, and miners. Miners verify blocks that contain payment data using electricity and mining equipment such as high-power computing chips. When a miner verifies a block and the block then enters the Bitcoin blockchain, the miner is compensated with BTC. When the block reward halving occurs, which happens every four years, it decreases the compensation miners receive by half. Prior to the 2020 halving, Bitcoin miners earned around 1,800 BTC every day. Post-halving, miners are expected to generate around 900 BTC per day. Bitcoin is a deflationary currency because of its fixed supply of 21 million BTC. As such, any occurrence that affects the supply of BTC will inevitably have a significant impact on its long-term price trend. In theory, the halving is likely to have a positive effect on the price of Bitcoin over the next four years. Less BTC will be mined by miners, which means less BTC will be sold to the market. But, as seen in the 2016 halving, the Bitcoin price tends to drop right before and after a halving occurs. A post-halving drop happens as whales move to take advantage of rising retail demand. In April, data shows that spot volume of Bitcoin rose noticeably on platforms like Coinbase and Binance. Hence, heading into the halving, the demand for Bitcoin from retail investors is higher than in previous months. For whales, this means liquidity. Whales that hold millions of dollars worth of Bitcoin cannot sell BTC when they do not see much buying demand in the market. Whales typically wait for BTC price to rise to a local high point, and then initiate a sell-off. It is for this reason that the Bitcoin price sees a large shift in trend and a predictable cycle. In the past three months, the Bitcoin price increased from $3,600 to $10,065, by nearly three-fold. Most of the buying demand came from spot exchanges that saw record high volume in late April. Whales that accumulated in the $3,000 to $4,000 range have the incentive to sell at $10,000 where there is high liquidity and retail demand. The high price also coincided with a positive narrative in halving, similar to October 2019 when Chinese President Xi Jinping encouraged the development of blockchain technology. At the time, the Bitcoin price abruptly rose from $7,700 to $10,500 within a 48-hour span. Given that Bitcoin trading remains prohibited in China, it is difficult to state that a fear of missing out (FOMO) hit the Chinese market and retail investors bought in. 

All data is taken from the source: https://www.ccn.com/

description.original:
Salt water and tides continue up-river within the St. Lawrence as far as Quebec City.  An exciting intersection of waters on the way upstream from the Atlantic Ocean to this provincial capital occurs as the Saguenay river triumphs through a dramatic fjord into the St. Lawrence.  
Six different varieties of whales are seen regularly at this junction, as well as seals and sea birds.  We hope to encounter whales from the water-level perzpective of a zodiac with just 6 passengers on this occasion.
AND WE DO~!  You'll see some coming up to greet us.
The Essipit native peoples run this outfit from Les Bergeronnes, Quebec...
Check out this experience.  In nature, nothing is predictable, but as our helmsman said:  "We had a GIFT."  So, we share an up close and personal greeting from humpback whales.

description.original:
Ten Awesome Adventures in Los Cabos
https://www.cabosfinest.com/blog-2/
First up we have something for everyone at Wild Canyon Adventures.
Wild Canyon is an adventure park located in the tourist corridor of Cabo San Lucas – San José del Cabo where you will find many activities and extreme sports. Within this huge adventure park, you will find the longest monster zip-lining in Baja! They also have “La Gondola” a funicular unique in its style with glass floors where you bungee jump and giant swing 300 feet above the ground. They have so many ways to play including off-roading tours, camel rides, moon zipping, and their new water park. The longest suspension bridge will also get your adrenaline pumping. Wild Canyon offers different combo packages and restaurant and bar.

Combo Horseback & ATV tour at Rancho Carisuva-
For over a decade Rancho Carisuva has hosted international guests to their oceanfront eco-park. They offer authentic ecological outdoor adventures just north of Cabo. The dedication to the animals is apparent as soon as you arrive in one of their air-conditioned vans. These happy horses, burros, and farm animals are friendly and smile at you while touring you through their amazing property. The combination of horseback and ATV tour is their most popular. You will spend the day discovering the Baja like it used to be. You will leave feeling satisfied that your contribution is directly used to maintain their well cared for animals, ranch, and help preserve the traditions of the magical land.

Book a Private Charter on Zigzag Catamaran.
Zig Zag is known in Cabo as the most luxurious sailing catamaran. Elegance and service along with great food and water toys make this a great way to spend a day on the ocean and Sea. They have 9 years of experience receiving groups from the most prestigious resorts. Their priority is to create a one of a kind customer experience so the guests can remember it as the highlight of their trip. How about sailing in the most extraordinary sunsets in Cabo? Your options are plenty with kayaks, SUP, snorkeling, whale watching, and more. Enjoy the scenery of Lovers Beach, Santa Maria Bay, and enjoy the Sea of Cortez that Jacque Cousteau nicknamed “The Aquarium of the World” all are waiting for you with s customized tour.

Whale Shark Encounter in La Paz.
Enjoy an outstanding ALL-INCLUSIVE cruise, on a large and spacious sailing catamaran, and snorkel with the largest fish in the world!
The whale shark filters surface water for microscopic plankton, which allows us to swim beside these rare and gentle giants. Baja Whale sharks are the premier tour of its kind, their all-inclusive whale shark excursion includes a cruise of approximately 4.5 to 5 hours, and includes savory chef-prepared meals, a skilled and educated crew, and a marine biologist as snorkel leader. We provide a powered support boat, bottled water, beer, sodas, an open bar, private bathrooms, fresh water showers, laundered towels, all the equipment, even reef-friendly sunscreen. We are NOT a cattle-car Tour operator. Truly a lifetime experience

Go Extreme Off-road with Wide Open Baja.
This is the ultimate off-road experience that is for the adrenaline-seeking adventurer. This is their full-day program from 8-10 hours you will travel across an array of Baja sceneries in a Baja Race Car. Be guided by experienced Baja racers and discover the hidden beauty of Los Cabos. You will discover one of the true challenges of extreme off-road travel.

Diving snd snorkeling tours in Cabo Pulmo Marine Park.
The village of Cabo Pulmo was established in 1987 and currently has a population of 114, the National Marine Park of Cabo Pulmo was established in 1995 to protect the oldest living Coral Reef in North America. Cabo Pulmo Dive Resort welcomes you to what is quickly becoming the biggest nature conservation success story in all of North America.
On the water, in the water or on land the natural beauty of Cabo Pulmo is a little piece of paradise. You will never forget having a local tour guide introduce you to the many popular marine sites. Their guides speak English & Spanish. 
Snorkeling and diving for age groups 8 and older. Treat yourself to a world-class marine sanctuary experience.   Their divemasters & instructors are PADI certified to introduce you to the many favorite marine sites.

Luxury Whale Watching Cruise with Cabo Adventures.
When it comes to spotting whales, Cabo San Lucas is a worldwide hotspot. That’s because the waters surrounding Cabo are breeding areas and migratory stops for whales in the Pacific Ocean. To help you get as close to these magnificent creatures as possible and take pictures the experts at Cabo Adventures proudly offer this one-of-a-kind luxury whale watching tour...
